<TEXT>
a subway car derailment that killed three 
people and injured 162 may have been triggered by a dragging motor 
that hit a track switch federal investigators said thursday 
the altered switch may have sent the last three cars in the 
sixcar train onto another set of tracks wednesday causing one car 
to be yanked into steel support beams said john k lauber of the 
national transportation safety board evidence indicated the motor 
dropped when a nut came loose lauber said adding that 
investigators were told that subway motors had dropped from their 
supports three times in the last 15 years most recently just a 
month ago 
that probably resulted in the pivoting of the motor under the 
car and that probably was the initiation of the accident he 
said 
a 37block section of west philadelphias 128mile subway and 
elevated train line a major commuter artery in the nations 
fifthlargest city remained closed thursday as federal 
investigators made their final inspection of the wreckage 
extra buses were pressed into service to handle some of the 
100000 people who typically ride the line twice a day 
the accident was the worst in the 21 years the commuter system 
has been operated by the southeastern pennsylvania transportation 
authority many of the cars on the line are 20 years old but all 
six on the train in the accident had been renovated in the last 
eight years septa said 
all three of the dead were among seven passengers trapped in the 
wreckage after three support beams tore into one car authorities 
said of the 162 people treated at 10 hospitals 16 remained 
hospitalized thursday two were in critical or serious condition 
the city medical examiners office identified two of the dead as 
denise devlin 34 and gospodin kanchev 52 both of philadelphia 
the third victim a 60yearold woman who died after her leg was 
amputated in an effort to free her from the wreckage remained 
unidentified 
the motor which was under the third car hit a crossover switch 
about 1500 feet after coming loose lauber said 
the philadelphia inquirer reported that problems with the bolts 
breaking led septa employees to brace the motors with bars 
harry knittel business agent with the transport workers union 
said the car with the suspect motor had been inspected once a month 
for at least the past 12 months and the last inspection had been 
feb 1 
theres only so much welding and repairs that 30yearold 
frames can take he told the news 
septa has ordered inspections of all older subway cars which 
date from the early 1960s 
ntsb investigators documented damage to cars and tracks made 
diagrams of seats examined training maintenance and operations 
records interviewed survivors and studied blueprints of the cars 
lauder said 
our people are underneath the car he said theyre 
crawling all over the car theyve been crawling underneath and 
around the sides and all over weve also been collecting bits and 
pieces from along the entire accident scene 
the ntsb gave septa permission to finish clearing the shattered 
glass and twisted metal left from the wreck 
septa put an extra 120 buses into service to deal with the 
service shutdown which also affected underground sections of a 
subwaysurface streetcar system 
subway support columns dating to about 1907 will be repaired if 
necessary septa said but lauder said there were no indications 
the beams had been damaged 
the ntsb has no regulatory powers but determines the probable 
cause of about 3000 plane crashes and other transportation 
accidents annually it recommends preventive steps to government 
agencies and industry 
</TEXT>
