<DOCNO> AP900308-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
in a shabby icecold meeting room behind 
a village store deep in the farmlands of southern poland 150 
people burst into patriotic song in german 
the sound is chilling to poles with vivid memories of the 
brutality of nazi occupiers and a history of partition by foreign 
powers 
but it is encouraged by the solidarityled government which is 
committed to recognizing polands ethnic diversity after decades of 
repression 
weve been negated for a long time we didnt exist we had 
to save ourselves says jan krol founder of the newly registered 
german cultural society he was in his 20s when his native gogolin 
became part of poland 
yet just as polands german minority is being acknowledged the 
debate over guaranteeing polands western border prior to german 
reunification is again stirring tensions between two nationalities 
that have often in their histories fought bloody battles over land 
with the assent of the other world war ii allies stalin created 
postwar polands western third from lands seized from the defeated 
nazis compensation for an even larger swath the soviets took from 
eastern poland 
millions of ethnic german nationals were expelled 14 million 
from the silesian region that includes gogolin and the acquired 
territory was resettled by the poles uprooted from the east 
communist governments in warsaw refused to acknowledge that 
hundreds of thousands of ethnic germans still lived in poland 
their secret police and vigorous discrimination worked to prevent 
any manifestation of german identity 
but under the redtile roofs of silesia german is spoken to 
this day and in some west german political circles these lands 
are still considered german 
west german chancellor helmut kohls reluctance to unequivocally 
renounce claims to silesia and commit a united germany to its 
current polish border along the oder and neisse rivers has strained 
relations with poland 
just five months ago kohl made a longplanned conciliatory 
visit to poland and prime minister tadeusz mazowiecki assured kohl 
that poland was committed to helping its german minority maintain 
its heritage 
four times since 1985 attempts by krol to register his cultural 
society had been rejected on feb 16 it was officially registered 
now the sitting room of his modest house without a telephone 
like most in this tiny hamlet is a beehive of activities to 
organize the estimated 300000 to 400000 ethnic german silesians 
we are facing a difficult task to get back what was taken away 
in 1945 our culture or language we are going to strive for 
that fight for that said the whitehaired raspyvoiced krol in 
an interview frequently interrupted by germanspeaking visitors 
bringing petitions 
when krols son henryk tried to become the only ethnic german 
to gain election to parliament there was an outburst of 
antigerman nationalism grafitti went up saying germans go 
home 
henryk lost the february byelection 
some poles are sympathetic to the german minoritys desire to 
practice its traditions but many are not suspecting aspirations 
are harbored for parts of poland to become german again 
we are willing to grant full rights to persons or groups of 
authentic german descent who profess their allegiance to german as 
their native tongue and to german tradition solidaritys jerzy 
wuttke chairman of parliaments ethnic minorities commission told 
tygodnik solidarnosc 
we will make sure however that those rights will not be 
abused to harm polands national interest he said 
poles who lost 6 million people during world war ii say it is 
unsettling to see banners proclaiming helmut you are our 
chancellor too greeting kohl some wonder if it is the better 
economic situation in germany that moves some ethnic germans to 
profess such allegiance 
when mostly older ethnic germans gathered late one recent 
afternoon in gogolin to organize their ranks they started by 
singing of heimat the homeland 
this is heimat its ours said the elder krol we 
were born here it is our home our family is here 
the krols and their neighbors say they hope their efforts will 
maintain a german presence in the region 
the younger people are waiting and watching to see what will 
happen now if it will be positive they have their suitcases 
packed said hubert materla who returned to gogolin in 1946 
after being released from an american prisonerofwar camp 
he said the secret police harassed him for speaking german and 
that of 16 people who tried to organize an ethnic german group in 
the early 1980s only he remains in poland 
for the krols materla and others in the community german 
reunification means the elimination of one border east germanys 
now crossed to visit the many including 70 percent of the krol 
family who have already left 
without expressing desire for change the krols stop short of 
affirming polands current territory 
very often i am asked like chancellor kohl about recognition 
of the oderneisse border said the younger krol the issue is 
very simple the border does exist today it would be difficult 
to imagine a similar resettlement of people it seems there is 
no other way he said 
added his father the hopes for any kind of border change are 
very small 
instead they say they seek german teachers for their schools 
there are many young people who speak polish but have german 
hearts said henryk krol a 41yearold veternarian who considers 
his german like a 5yearolds 
and they want to win representation in may elections for local 
governments villages that are 90 percent german dot the region 
</TEXT>
