<TEXT>
the midday sun seems about to burn 
holes in the streets of the capital the dryseason wind blows dust 
against stillbright election slogans painted in yellow on curbs 
and daubed red and blue on the sides of dilapidated buildings 
the feb 25 election spelled the defeat of nicaraguas leftist 
sandinista government if all goes as planned power will be 
transferred next month to a largely conservative opposition 
coalition which says it will use freemarket tactics to rescue the 
country from economic collapse 
the task will be a mighty one each side in the election had its 
own view of nicaraguas future but they agree about the grimness 
of its present a largely agrarian potentially prosperous nation 
where war inflation and unemployment have brought many close to 
despair 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
managua used to have a downtown before the earthquake of 1972 
those streets now see only a trickle of people walking past 
boardedup buildings and vacant lots filled with scrub 
the national cathedral has looked like a medieval ruin since the 
quake its gothic arches roofless soaring into the sky 
families live in the downtown now pigs and chickens wandering 
in crude courtyards beside their shacks within sight of a 
modernistic new convention center one of downtowns few 
attractions a naked toddler and his raggedly dressed brothers and 
sisters play in the street on a 90degree day 
inside a crumbling downtown building that somehow survived the 
quake a sandinistaorganized collective works busily women 
hunched over sewing machines 
the sandinistas built collectives throughout the country 
calling them an answer to capitalist exploitation of workers they 
also built schools and health clinics and told workers that they 
were finally masters of their country 
a slogan painted on a cracked outside panel of the sewing 
collectives building reads we are free now we will never be 
slaves again 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
at the gracious home of violeta barrios de chamorro nicaraguas 
presidentelect a houseman brings coffee and cocacola for 
visitors the house is nondescript from the street but inside it 
spreads into a handsome mansion flowing gracefully from interior 
rooms into a garden with twisting paths and plants dramatically 
backlit at night 
sitting in a dark study crammed with memorabilia her left leg 
in a cast from a recent knee operation the 60yearold 
silverhaired mrs chamorro says she is certain her uno coalition 
can solve nicaraguas problems she promises to abolish the 
sandinista military draft and put the country back to work but she 
is characteristically vague about details she often says they are 
in the hands of her advisers 
as her visitors leave one of them asks if with the bitterly 
fought election just over her biggest troubles running the 
country are really only now beginning 
leaning on her crutches mrs chamorro smiles 
youre such a pessimist she says 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
raul solorzano who runs a plastics plant in managua and serves 
in the local chamber of industry is optimistic mrs chamorros 
coalition is going to get business running again he says and the 
country will prosper after near economic ruin under the sandinistas 
we want the united states to help he says but if it 
doesnt he says nicaraguas private sector will rebuild the 
country by itself 
the accomplishments of the sandinista revolution he says were 
few people received land to live on but basic services like water 
and sanitation never appeared the sandinistas never understood 
economics he says and failed to generate money for improvements 
they wanted to make 
one thing is for certain solorzano says this country is 
through with communism people here will never be communists 
again 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
at the shiny olof palme convention center sandinista leader 
daniel ortega in jeans and a dark blueandred striped shirt is 
very much defending the accomplishments of the revolution 
addressing the inter american press association he makes no 
apology for what the sandinistas have done in nearly 11 years since 
they overthrew dictator anastasio somoza sandinistas say the 
revolution would have accomplished even more if the government had 
not had to fight a war against the usbacked contras 
after the 25th of april i shall be in the opposition ortega 
says i shall be in constructive not destructive opposition 
but he warns that he and the sandinistas who will hold the 
biggest single bloc of votes in the new national assembly are 
determined to strengthen and carry forward what the sandinistas 
have done so far 
today we are facing a very difficult situation he says 
and it will depend on the maturity of those who rule and those 
who are ruled to take the country on the road to development and 
peace 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a sandinista mural on a downtown street shows a grotesque statue 
of liberty hands transformed into talons trying to strangle the 
nicaraguan revolution helping is a grim reaper clad in an 
american flag 
the sandinista election campaign hammered home the claim that a 
vote for the opposition was a vote for us domination and a return 
to the brutal rule of s them back said dana neal 
some 6300 bus drivers and 3000 maintenance and office workers 
walked off the job friday after talks broke down over a new 
threeyear contract 
the company has been operating at reduced levels using about 
700 replacement drivers plus union members who crossed picket 
lines the company says about 350 union drivers are at work the 
union says 95 returned 
the cause of this strike is singular union spokesman 
jeffery nelson said after wednesdays talks the company has 
refused to negotiate with the union that represents its 9000 
employees in good faith 
in other developments wednesday 
sen howard metzenbaum dohio and 10 other senators asked 
labor secretary elizabeth dole to intervene as she did in last 
years pittston coal strike by appointing a supermediator a 
spokeswoman for mrs dole said she had no such plans because the 
dispute is still under the normal mediation process 
in redding calif about 500 mourners half of them striking 
drivers in uniform marched in memory of a driver killed on a 
picket line the mourners were led by the widow of 59yearold 
robert waterhouse who was pinned against a building saturday by a 
bus operated by a replacement driver no charges were filed 
in richmond va david w batchelor president of greyhounds 
eastern division reiterated the companys position that the 
replacement drivers are permanent hires and that strikers who 
return will get jobs only as slots become available 
the company obtained its 12th temporary restraining order 
prohibiting violence vandalism and interference with operations 
several such incidents have occurred since the strike began 
including shots fired at buses in chicago and windows and mirrors 
smashed in other cities 
court orders have been granted in chicago cincinnati 
cleveland des moines iowa jacksonville fla los angeles mount 
laurel nj philadelphia pittsburgh portland ore sacramento 
calif and san francisco 
</TEXT>
