<TEXT>
poor people who live and work in rural areas 
would benefit more than city dwellers from several proposed 
antipoverty programs according to a report released today 
the study by the center on budget and policy priorities notes 
that a disproportionate share of working poor live in rural areas 
although only 23 percent of the nation is rural 33 percent of the 
working poor live in rural areas it said 
rep mike synar dokla whose states poverty rate increased 
from 134 percent in the early 1980s to 155 percent by the middle 
of the decade said some of the centers recommendations would cost 
more than the country can afford now 
however there are smaller steps we can take and have taken 
to begin to meet the needs of the rural working poor said synar 
who released the study along with sen james jeffords rvt 
the report suggested aiding the working poor by 
enlarging the earned income tax credit for lowincome families 
with children 
extending the child care tax credit to lowincome working 
families 
restoring the minimum wage to its average purchasing power 
during the 1960s and 1970s 
partially reversing cutbacks made during the 1980s in the 
unemployment insurance program 
expanding medicaid so it can provide health care coverage to 
more children in working poor families 
the earned income tax credit available to low and 
moderateincome families with children offers an example of how 
rural working poor benefit more from such programs than those in 
the city 
to receive the credit which was worth up to 910 in 1989 
families need only to file a federal income tax return the family 
either gets a tax break or if the familys income is too low to be 
taxed the government sends a check for the appropriate amount 
since wages are lower in rural than in urban areas and since 
a larger proportion of the rural poor work the proportion of 
families qualifying for the tax credit is higher in rural than in 
urban locations said the center 
legislation to increase the amount of money available under the 
earned income tax credit is pending in the house 
if the minimum wage were increased to give it the same 
purchasing power it had 20 or 30 years ago a larger share of rural 
workers would benefit than city dwellers said the report because 
one in three rural workers earn at or near the minimum wage 
compared with about one in five urban workers 
expansion of the earned income credit combined with full 
restoration of the minimum wage would lift a substantial number of 
rural working poor households out of poverty said robert 
greenstein center director and coauthor of the report 
providing extended unemployment benefits in areas of states with 
very high unemployment even if the state as a whole doesnt 
qualify would help rural areas where unemployment is often 
seasonal he said 
currently extended benefits may be provided to the longterm 
unemployed only when the statewide jobless rate is very high 
the report is one in a series of rural poverty reports by the 
center on budget and policy priorities an independent research 
organization that specializes in the analysis of data and policy 
issues affecting low and moderateincome americans 
