lt gen prosper avril spoke wednesday as thousands of students 
rallied in provincial cities for the second straight day to protest 
the armys killing of an 11yearold girl 
the girl was to be buried today and student groups called for a 
national day of mourning eleven political parties urged businesses 
and factories to close in sympathy 
asked in a rare interview whether he might resign avril said 
i will never resist the will of the people but he added we 
must get on with elections because elections reflect the will of 
the people 
if i step down hurriedly it will create a lot of turmoil 
avril said at the presidential palace i have thought a lot about 
how to prevent the country falling into revolution and chaos 
on wednesday thousands of students marched in the provincial 
towns of jacmel jeremie leogane petit goave and mirebalais the 
roman catholic churchs radio soleil reported 
in gonaives 100 miles north of the capital portauprince 
schools stayed closed for a second day and students set up flaming 
tire barricades 
schools were also closed in the northern coastal city of 
caphaitien radio soleil said 
the student marches were reminiscent of demonstrations in 
november 1985 to protest the armys killing of three high school 
students in gonaives those protests led to the downfall of former 
dictator jeanclaude duvalier who fled to exile in france in 
february 1986 
avril a former duvalier aide came to power in september 1988 
replacing lt gen henri namphy in a coup led by lowerranking 
soldiers 
he promised elections and reforms but shipped seven 
prodemocracy leaders into exile during a crackdown in january and 
arrested more than 50 opposition activists some of whom were 
beaten in custody 
avril who has promised presidential elections later this year 
said he imposed a state of siege jan 20 as a preventive 
measure after the killing of an army colonel because the 
electoral process itself was threatened 
he lifted the emergency nine days later after an international 
outcry 
on wednesday the un human rights commission agreed to begin a 
special investigation into allegations of abuses in haiti saying 
the situation under avril remains disturbing and even seems to 
have deteriorated 
the genevabased organization said it was alarmed by the 
proliferation of acts of violence in haiti particularly against 
arrested or detained persons and by the apparent inability of the 
judicial system to put an end to such acts 
virtually all political parties and unions have vowed to boycott 
any elections under avril they say he cant be trusted to turn 
over power to elected civilians 
eighteen parties have proposed that avril be replaced by a 
supreme court justice until a new leader is elected 
if there is a change of government that will only delay 
elections even more avril said 
in the interview avril repeated his promise to allow elections 
this year and abide by the results avril repeated he was not 
interested in running for office 
county and municipal elections are scheduled for april 29 
legislative elections july 22 and presidential elections oct 28 
in november 1987 the first free general elections since 
independence from france in 1804 were canceled after attackers 
protected by soldiers massacred at least 34 voters 
this weeks student marches began tuesday to protest the death 
of 11yearold roseline vaval she was studying on her porch when 
she was fatally shot monday by a soldier breaking up a small 
antigovernment demonstration in petit goave 
</TEXT>
