<TEXT>
real estate problems in the northeast are 
dragging down bank profits and some analysts worry the weakness 
will spread 
banks earned 27 billion in the fourth quarter and 163 
billion for all of 1989 a 34 percent drop from 248 billion in 
1988 the federal deposit insurance corp said wednesday 
provisions for loan losses hit a nearrecord 303 billion last 
year the fdic attributed about twothirds of that to domestic 
loans primarily for real estate development third world loan 
problems caused the rest 
five of the countrys 10 largest banks were in the red last 
year primarily because of provisions for losses on developing 
country loans they were chase manhattan morgan guaranty 
manufacturers hanover bankers trust and chemical bank 
bad real estate loans more than doubled in the northeast where 
four states massachusetts connecticut new hampshire and new 
york were among the 10 with the highest percentage of sour real 
estate loans 
the bostonbased bank of new england alone lost 11 billion 
last year most of it in real estate 
problem real estate continued to cause losses in the southwest 
but institutions in that region appear to be recovering somewhat 
texas losses for instance totaled 537 million last year down 
from 21 billion in 1988 
despite the downturn banks outside the southwest poured money 
into real estate loans particularly in the asyetuntroubled 
southeast and west real estate lending increased 128 percent 
nationally compared with a 54 percent growth rate for bank assets 
generally 
the chairman of the fdic l william seidman called attention 
to the real estate figures but declined to predict if the situation 
would deepen or spread this year private analysts were less 
reticent 
we are in a particularly vicious real estate cycle said 
economist paul getman of regional financial associates of west 
chester pa i think youre going to get more bad news 
particularly in the southeast in florida georgia the carolinas 
because there was a lot of speculative buying there 
i think youll see continued problems in the northeast and on 
a selected basis in the southeast said alex sheshunoff an 
austin texasbased analyst the big question mark is california 
how long can they continue to maintain high prices for real 
estate 
meanwhile in a separate report the office of thrift 
supervision said net withdrawals from savings institutions totaled 
86 billion in december bringing outflows for all of 1989 to a 
record 736 billion 
december marked the 18th outflow in 19 months and was the 
biggest drain since september when withdrawals excluding interest 
credited totaled 88 billion 
outflows for the year were the largest on record the last big 
outflow 254 billion occurred in 1981 when interest rates at 
competing moneymarket mutual funds skyrocketed at a time when 
thrift rates were capped by law 
what youre seeing now is unprecedented but its not 
surprising said economist martin regalia of the national council 
of savings institutions 
early in the year the industry lost deposits in part because 
sampl problems had shaken customers confidence but economists say 
the shrinkage in the last half of the year is almost entirely a 
response to tough new financial standards in president bushs sampl 
bailout enacted last august 
the rules require thrifts to back their lending with more of 
their owners money most cant raise the capital as a result 
they must trim their balance sheets 
thrifts shed 256 billion in assets in december with 46 
billion of that coming at sampls under government control and almost 
threefourths of the remainder at weakly capitalized thrifts still 
operating independently 
sampl assets at the end of the year totaled 125 trillion down 
100 billion 73 percent from a year earlier in contrast 
commercial bank assets grew 54 percent to 33 trillion 
i think the sampl downsizing is going to continue throughout 
1990 and maybe into 1991 as well although we might see some ebbing 
of the pace regalia said 
