<TEXT>
senate leaders and the bush administration are 
trying to hold together a compromise clean air bill amid criticism 
by some lawmakers that automobile emission controls are too weak 
about a dozen senators were preparing to introduce today a 
string of amendments that would toughen pollution controls from 
auto tailpipes and require carmakers to produce more fuelefficient 
vehicles 
the provisions are opposed by the administration as well as the 
senates democratic and republican leadership 
as senators considered a number of minor changes to the 
legislation wednesday white house and industry lobbyists tried to 
head off any major reworking of the bill which was the product of 
three weeks of closeddoor negotiations 
the legislation calls for sweeping regulations on smogcausing 
pollution from automobiles and industries requires controls on 191 
toxic industrial chemicals and requires cuts in acid rain 
pollutants from coalburning electric utility plants and factories 
as part of the compromise a second round of automatic tailpipe 
controls and a fuel economy provision were deleted from the 
legislation the auto industry has maintained that both 
requirements were too expensive and perhaps not attainable 
but several senators said wednesday they would attempt to revive 
the tougher provisions on the senate floor 
transportation secretary samuel skinner said in a letter that 
the fuel economy proposal would have a devastating impact on 
the auto industry and consumers forcing automakers to concentrate 
on making smaller cars 
proponents contended that new controls on carbon dioxide are 
needed to deal with global warming carbon dioxide is responsible 
for nearly half of the greenhouse effect and motor vehicles are 
the largest single source of carbon dixoide emissions said sen 
albert gore dtenn 
meanwhile some republican senators complained late wednesday 
that the complex bill was being pushed through the senate too 
quickly 
sen william armstrong rcolo suggested that the bill was 
being rammed down our throats and he and sen ted stevens 
ralaska expressed doubt that it could be completed soon 
but majority leader george mitchell dmaine said he wants to 
finish the bill by the end of the week and might call the senators 
into session saturday to get the job done 
the senate begins a weeklong recess next week and mitchell 
expressed concern that if debate on the legislation extends to 
after the recess the compromise might fall apart 
meanwhile the senators meeting until nearly midnight 
wednesday approved and rejected a number of amendments mostly by 
voice vote with little debate 
among the amendments approved were provisions 
exempting fertilizer from certain reporting requirements and 
agricultural tanks from other requirements under the toxic 
pollution section of the bill 
continuing the authority of the environmental protection agency 
to regulate radioactive emissions along with the nuclear 
regulatory commission the amendment also would allow states to 
continue to impose more stringent standards on radioactive 
emissions than federal standards 
in the first roll call vote on the bill during the three days it 
has been on the floor the senate voted 5343 to let stand a 
section of the bill that favors ethanol as part of an oxygenated 
fuels program 
critics of the provision had claimed it unfairly promotes 
ethanol which is made from corn as opposed to other fuels such a 
methanol supporters including most farm state senators said 
those concerns were unfounded 
the provision requires that in areas not meeting federal air 
quality standards gasoline must have a 31 percent oxygen content 
during winter months opponents of the measure had sought to lower 
than to 27 percent saying that would open the way for a broader 
range of fuel blends and not just an ethanol blend 
</TEXT>
