<TEXT>
jacqueline kennedy onassis ended a 
10year dispute with a group of wampanoag indians by agreeing to 
give them a plot of land and 100000 in exchange for a tiny 
beachfront site 
the case pitted mrs onassis desire for privacy against the 
indians belief that they should retain control of tribal lands on 
marthas vineyard including 15 acres owned primarily by the 
wampanoags that is surrounded by onassis estate on the island 
after all this time im just happy the land was settled 
said thelma weissberg one of the 25 descendants of william 
vanderhoop a wampanoag who lived in the area in the 1870s and 
owned the 15acre plot ive lived on the island all my life and 
im happy that we have some of our land back 
wampanoags have lived at the picturesque cliffs of gay head for 
centuries the tribe believes the tract on onassis estate holds 
the last resting place of the great chief moshup and his wife 
squant 
in 1980 mrs onassis obtained onesixth interest in the 
15acre plot and sought to buy the remaining fivesixths from the 
25 descendants of vanderhoop she wanted to close access to the 
parcel and keep beachgoers and tourists away from her 400acre 
property 
but the wampanoags resisted and a series of lawsuits and 
countersuits followed 
according to the terms of the agreement signed wednesday the 
wampanoags will surrender title and access to the 15acre site in 
exchange for 100000 and a 2acre beachfront plot closer to the 
nearest road 
brian hurley one of mrs onassis attorneys said shes just 
pleased to have resolved this long matter and hopes to continue 
being good neighbors she wants to put it behind her 
since 1974 various wampanoags have regained about 400 acres of 
what they consider tribal land on marthas vineyard through a 
series of federal lawsuits 
they claimed that a 1790 law that forbids transfer of indian 
lands without federal approval was violated in the 1870s when the 
state redistributed tribal lands to other island residents 
the wampanoags have maintained a tribal structure for more than 
370 years according to tribal council president donald widdiss 
but they did not receive federal recognition until 1987 there are 
only 250 wampanoags left at gay head and only 630 in the nation 
