reaction said audris siaurusavicius a reporter for rebirth the 
sajudis newspaper 
if there were no such proposal on the presidency we wouldnt 
have done this now 
all three baltic republics latvia lithuania and estonia were 
independent nations between the world wars before being forced to 
join the soviet union in 1940 while under soviet occupation 
lawmakers in moscow are considering a proposed law that would 
give republics the right to secede from the union but settling 
financial issues is just one of a daunting series of requirements 
that the republics would have to meet in order to secede 
the proposed law also says a republic can secede only after a 
republicwide referendum in which threefourths of the adults vote 
in favor of the move then the secession proposal must be submitted 
to national lawmakers in moscow 
during a minimum fiveyear transition phase defense security 
and border questions are to be settled and the government of the 
seceding republic must also settle financial and property issues 
the soviet constitution guarantees republics the right to 
secede but the procedure never has been spelled out in soviet law 
siaurusavicius said sajudis leaders were expecting moscows 
response to the declaration to be restrained but he said the 
republic could already feel the effects of a mounting soviet 
economic blockade many factories are running short on raw 
materials and they expect the situation to get worse 
gorbachev has repeatedly denounced separatists and has asked 
activists to give moscow time to work out the terms of a new soviet 
federation before moving to secede 
an article in the government newspaper izvestia on wednesday 
complained that lithuania is getting public opinion used to the 
fact that it is leaving without thinking through all the 
economic and political difficulties secession would create 
the article said such problems would include trade imbalances 
the difficulty of deciding what to do about various sovietbuilt 
factories and the fate of lithuanian residents who want to retain 
their soviet citizenship 
moreover it said the lithuanian push for independence had 
spread to other republics one after another legislative 
measures are passed which like a lancet cut off vein after vein 
nerve after nerve from the overall organism the article said 
about half of the soviet unions 15 republics now have popular 
groups pushing for independence or greater sovereignty including 
moldavia georgia armenia azerbaijan estonia and latvia 
