be struck with republicans 
i expect that the leadership will propose a comprehensive 
substitute amendment to what we passed the panels chairman 
sen wendell ford dky said of the democratic proposal that 
would impose voluntary spending caps ranging from 16 billion to 
92 billion on individual senate candidates 
the committee approved the bill on a 73 partyline vote 
republicans supported a bipartisan advisory panels call to limit 
how much candidates can raise from political action committees 
pacs and outofstate donors but place no limit on instate 
contributions from inidviudals 
sen ted stevens ralaska called the recommendations wednesday 
from the panel of six experts appointed by senate demnocratic 
leader george mitchell of maine and republican leader bob dole a 
genius solution 
republicans plan to begin work next week on a bill based on the 
panels recommendations but said they will add a provision to 
address unreported soft money contributions by nonparty 
interest groups such as labor unions corporations and nonprofit 
organizations 
the panel endorsed individual candidate spending ceilings sought 
by democrats but with reasonably high and flexible limits and 
a provision that would let the gop keep using its advantage in 
raising money through mass direct mailings 
under the panels plan individual candidates could exceed the 
limits through an exemption for limited donations from instate 
residents and still qualify for the discount mail and television 
advertising rates intended to lure compliance 
