fundamentally flawed 
no serious reform of the congressional campaign finance system 
is possible unless the role and influence of pac money is 
dramatically reduced and the soft money system has brought back 
watergatesize and watergatestyle contributions into federal 
campaigns is shut down wertheimer said 
the experts three each picked by mitchell and dole supported 
republican desires for unfettered party spending on phone banks 
voter registration and direct mail campaigns and higher limits on 
individual contributions 
the report recommended a compromise on pacs opposing president 
bushs call for an outright ban on corporate and union pacs that 
have overwhelmingly favored democratic incumbents instead it 
recommended diminishing their role 
pacs could contribute only up to onethird of a candidates 
spending limit under the panels proposals from then on their 
contributions to each candidate would be limited to half the 
current 10000 limit for primary and general election campaigns 
together 
the panel also would ban pacs from making postelection 
contributions to retire a candidates campaign debt and restrict 
labor and corporate pacs in bundling or gathering donations on 
behalf of a candidate 
however it found little obvious cause for concern in 
bundling done by individuals such as the more than 200000 raised 
in campaign gifts raised by phoenix savings and loan executive 
charles h keating jr for five us senators 
other campaign financing abuses raised by last years sampl crisis 
also were ignored by the panel including the use of socalled 
leadership pacs by senior party officials to raise money for other 
candidates 
it also had no recommendation on taxexempt foundations of the 
13 million keating contributed to five senate candidates 
850000 was through a taxexempt voter registration foundation 
headed by the son of sen alan cranston dcalif 
