<TEXT>
the first major study of women and heart 
disease is being undertaken by the johns hopkins medical 
institution and six other centers after decades of research 
devoted solely to male heart disease 
the 10 million fouryear study is designed to determine 
whether three different hormones can help reduce heart disease in 
postmenopausal women heart disease kills more americans than any 
other disease 
in the study 840 women will be assigned at random to one of the 
three medications or to a placebo high blood cholesterol 
hypertension and heightened levels of a bloodclotting factor will 
be studied 
the results could prompt doctors to prescribe hormone therapy 
for postmenopausal women said dr trudy bush an epidemiologist 
at the johns hopkins school of hygiene and public health 
in my opinion there is good evidence at this time that women 
who use estrogens probably have about half the risk of heart 
disease compared to women who dont bush said estrogen hormones 
will be part of the study 
bush is heading the study at hopkins along with gynecologists 
dr david foster and dr howard zacur 
in the past major studies of heart disease in the united states 
have involved males because the ailment tends to strike men at a 
younger age than women and younger people are less likely to 
suffer from additional health problems that could complicate a 
study 
the new study called postmenopausal estrogen and progestin 
intervention reflects a belief that women have been denied equal 
time in health studies as well as a growing emphasis on the health 
of older people 
underlying the study is the belief that estrogen a hormone 
needed for normal female sexual development protects younger women 
against heart disease researchers also suspect the threat of a 
heart attack increases during menopause when estrogen production 
drops off 
the study will try to determine whether hormone drugs take the 
place of natural estrogen in protecting the hearts of older women 
</TEXT>
