<TEXT>
a federal judge has ruled that the reagan 
administration acted within the constitution when in 1984 it barred 
family planning aid to private foreign organizations that perform 
abortions 
it is within the executive branchs plenary authority over 
foreign affairs to disassociate the united states completely from 
foreign organizations based upon their views or activities us 
district judge john walker said in a decision wednesday 
walker made the finding in dismissing a lawsuit by the planned 
parenthood federation of america challenging the policy 
the policy which was adopted by the agency for international 
development in 1984 and continued under president bush requires 
that foreign private health agencies in return for american 
grants certify that they did not perform or actively promote 
abortion as a method of family planning 
planned parenthood which assists private foreign agencies had 
charged that the policy was a violation of their first amendment 
right to advocate abortion and interfered with the rights of 
privacy of people seeking family planning information 
roger evans planned parenthoods director of litigation said 
the organization would appeal the judges ruling 
the ruling was the second time walker had dismissed the lawsuit 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals sent the lawsuit back to 
walker saying he must decide the constitutional questions of free 
speech and free association of american workers overseas who are 
affected by the policy 
