<TEXT>
charlotte m sitterly an astrophysicist who 
discovered one of the unstable elements in sunlight has died of 
heart failure 
mrs sitterly who was 91 died in her washington home last 
saturday she was considered one of the worlds foremost 
authorities on the composition of the sun 
her discovery of technetium an element changed scientific 
explanations of conditions in the suns interior 
her research focused on the study of the suns spectrum 
including shortwavelengths that could not penetrate the atmosphere 
and could only be observed from rockets 
she was born charlotte emma moore in ercildoun in chester 
county pa and married bancroft walker sitterly a colleague at 
the princeton university observatory in 1937 they had no 
children and he is deceased 
mrs sitterly was a phi beta kappa graduate in mathematics from 
swarthmore college in 1920 she earned her doctorate from the 
university of california at berkeley writing a thesis on the 
spectra of sunspots 
she worked as an astrophysicist with the department of 
commerces bureau of national standards and wrote many works on 
solar and atomic spectra 
mrs sitterly was cited as one of the first recipients of the 
federal womans award and was the first woman elected as a foreign 
associate by the royal astronomical society of london in 1949 
