the government will begin paying for certain 
liver transplants in medicare beneficiaries health and human 
services secretary louis sullivan announced thursday 
medicare is expected to spend 10 million for the operations in 
the first year and 120 million by the fifth year as more 
hospitals gain approval for reimbursement under the liver 
transplant program 
but sulliivan said the net impact on the medicare budget would 
be lower because the transplants will save the costs of treating 
patients with advanced liver disease he did not estimate the 
expected savings 
under the proposed rule medicare payment would allowed for 
transplants in patients with primary biliary cirrhosis primary 
sclerosing cholangitis hepatitis b antigen negative or 
postnecrotic cirrhosis alcoholic cirrhosis alpha1 antitrypsin 
deficiency disease wilsons disease and primary hemochromatosis 
a public health service study found liver transplants are safe 
and effective in treating those conditions in adults 
more than 3500 liver transplants have been performed in the 
united states 
to qualify for payment under the program a hospital must have a 
written patientselection process for choosing patients for whom 
the operation is most likely to be successful 
they also must show that at least 77 percent of their adult 
patients with the conditions covered under the program survive for 
at least one year after receiving a new liver and that 60 percent 
of them live at least two years 
the process is similar to the system used to approve hospitals 
for performing heart transplants on medicare beneficiaries the 
department said 
after a 60day period for public comment a final regulation 
will be published in the federal register and become effective 
