she has been branded as a crook and a thief everyone thinks 
of her as that woman with the shoes spence said in a recent 
telephone interview 
nearly every evening she visits the tomb of her late husband 
former philippines president ferdinand marcos the visits are timed 
to avoid tourists 
on wednesday night mrs marcos broke her silence saying in an 
interview that she is a misunderstood nervous and lonely widow 
and fears standing trial now that her defense team has been shaken 
up 
washington attorney richard hibey withdrew from the case less 
than a month before her federal trial in new york was scheduled to 
begin 
i dont know how my present lawyers can familiarize themselves 
with more than three years of litigation just before my trial 
she said this is most unjust and so detrimental to my defense 
hibey and attorney sandor frankel of new york withdrew after 
prosecutors said hibey faced a possible conflict of interest 
because they intended to call one of his partners as a witness 
us district judge john keenan delayed the start of the trial 
for six days to march 20 
mrs marcos and her husband who died in september were charged 
in october 1988 with fraud and racketeering counts accusing them of 
stealing more than 100 million from the philippine treasury to buy 
art and real estate they also were charged with defrauding banks 
of 165 million in loans 
defense attorneys say the key to mrs marcos defense is proving 
that the marcoses were forced out of the philippines during a 1986 
popular revolt with a promise of safe haven in the united states 
and that they did not leave willingly even though protesters 
threatened to overrun the presidential palace 
chief prosecutor charles labella refused to comment on the case 
although exile in hawaii has meant a series of indignities 
life was never bleaker than after marcos died mrs marcos said 
she added that mounting medical funeral and legal expenses and 
philippine president corazon aquinos refusal to let him be buried 
in his homeland also were discouraging 
the late dictator ruled the philippines for two decades 
most of the marcos alleged billions of dollars in assets have 
been frozen as part of the criminal indictment and because of more 
than a dozen civil lawsuits accusing the marcoses of acts ranging 
from corruption to murder 
mrs marcos refused to say where she gets her money allowing 
only that millions of dollars in legal and medical bills remain 
unpaid and that she relies on the goodwill of friends to stay 
afloat 
the us government does not control mrs marcos spending 
habits but requires her to submit a monthly accounting and receive 
special permission if she wants to spend more than 10000 a month 
marcos aides who spoke on condition of anonymity said the budget 
has fallen sharply from a high of about 200000 a month shortly 
after the marcoses fled here 
one source of money is mrs marcos daughter irene araneta who 
lives in woodside calif and is married to the son of a wealthy 
filipino industrialist aides said 
marcos spokesman roger peyuan said the marcoses have accumulated 
more than 3 million in legal bills he said the household staff of 
about 30 is paid irregularly but remains loyal because the marcoses 
have helped us so much and this is when she really needs us 
its very difficult to be a widow to be alone for the first 
time mrs marcos said i must admit that ferdinand handled all 
of this money business everything like that we led a very 
compartmentalized life 
during the interview at her home she appeared at times nervous 
apprehensive and lonely wringing her hands and fidgeting only to 
turn hopeful philosophical and reminiscent giggling and reading 
romantic inscriptions on cards from someone who signed them 
andy 
she recalled her past with no regret 
everything in life comes in pairs good and bad day and 
night yin and yang she said ferdinand always said you 
cannot argue with destiny just stay on top of it im just trying 
to keep control of my life 
