<TEXT>
the government on thursday introduced legislation 
to enable prosecutors to charge three aging emigres as nazi war 
criminals and police said they probably will set up a special unit 
to investigate more suspects 
the nazihunting simon wiesenthal center said britain was 
finally on the threshold of meting out justice to the suspects 
eastern europeans who fled after world war ii and became 
naturalized britons 
government officials said they hoped the war crimes bill would 
be passed by the summer raising the prospect of the first trial as 
early as years end 
but critics declared the bill was a revenge measure that would 
result in emotional and unfair show trials 
legislating in a spirit of revenge rarely produces good 
said governing conservative party lawmaker robert adley a leading 
critic of the government move 
the idea of hounding three old men to court will either finish 
up in farce or tragedy for those conducting this vendetta he 
added 
the bill followed a dec 12 vote by the house of commons to 
accept a governmentordered inquiry that said there was sufficient 
evidence to prosecute three suspects living in britain 
the report urged the investigation of 124 more cases of suspects 
who came to britain with thousands of displaced persons after the 
end of the 193945 war 
scotland yard londons police headquarters said there is a 
likelihood of scotland yard investigation team being set up to 
deal exclusively with war crime cases 
two eminent lawyers who conducted the inquiry for the government 
said britain must change its law to allow prosecutions of british 
citizens for crimes committed abroad or risk becoming a safe 
haven for nazis 
britain is the last allied country to take action australia and 
canada passed legislation in the past few years and are holding 
their first trials while the us justice department investigates 
and deports suspects for trial in israel 
prime minister margaret thatcher supports prosecutions 
but the government will allow a free vote according to 
conscience and not along party lines on the bill the key 
legislative stage the second reading is scheduled for march 19 
the los angelesbased simon wiesenthal center which submitted 
initial lists of suspects to the british government in 1986 urged 
britain to set up a special nazihunting unit similar to the us 
office of special investigations it includes historians and 
archivists 
but what is important is that the british government and the 
british parliament have now finally entered the threshold where 
justice is about to be done in respect of nazi war criminals 
said rabbi marvin hier dean of the center 
hier estimated the first trial could begin about three months 
after the bill becomes law 
the names of the suspects were kept confidential in a separate 
section of the report by the british investigators issued in july 
but one suspect antanas gecas a lithuanianborn retired mining 
engineer who lives in scotland has been identified repeatedly by 
the british news media 
gecas 73 acknowledges serving in a notorious police battalion 
in nazioccupied lithuania but says he only watched the atrocities 
all the suspects in britain are from lithuania or two other 
soviet republics ukraine and latvia where locals manned mobile 
death squads set up by the nazis the squads rounded up and 
murdered tens of thousands of jews 
the trials would involve new rules of evidence in britain to 
allow videotaping of testimony by aging witnesses in the soviet 
union and depositions left by witnesses who have since died 
