<TEXT>
the united states acting at the request of 
the late soviet dissident andrei sakharov will participate in a 
soviet project using a large orbiting radio telescope to peer into 
the core of quasars and other active galaxies it was announced 
thursday 
this is a small but significant step in the evolving 
cooperation in space activities between our two nations said 
vice president dan quayle announcing the us role at a ceremony 
with soviet ambassador yuri dubinin 
shortly before his death last year sakharov had written to 
nasas administrator richard truly asking the united states to 
take part in the program known as radioastron 
the project calls for the soviets to launch a 10meter radio 
telescope into earth orbit in 1993 it will work synchronously with 
us groundbased telescopes to produce unprecedented resolution 
for peering deep into space the vice presidents office said 
the united states will provide precision tracking facilities for 
very high accuracy measurements of the soviet satellite orbit in 
addition the united states will lend the soviets data recorders 
now being developed by the national radio astronomy observatory 
space is an area where in the past we have had competition 
with the soviet union quayle said and with the reduction of 
tensions perhaps this will be a place where we can have not 
competition but cooperation 
dubinin called the us participation a good start toward an 
era of cooperation 
