<TEXT>
a ninenation conference on north 
sea pollution ended thursday with agreement on lowering dangerous 
emissions but left some countries angry with britains stand on 
sewage dumping and undersea nuclear waste storage 
the coastal states pledged to reduce emissions of mercury lead 
cadmium and dioxins by 70 percent in 1995 and to phase out by 
decades end pcbs or polychlorinated biphenyls believed to be 
among the most hazardous materials made by man 
in a grudging concession to britain the dumping of sewage 
sludge will be allowed until 1998 while british industry will be 
allowed to dump until 1993 an annual 205000 to 270000 tons of 
industrial waste into the north sea one of the worlds most 
contaminated saltwater bodies 
we were very disappointed that the united kingdom could not 
follow us on this point said hanja maijweggen the dutch 
transport minister and conference chairman we hope the british 
will be more flexible the next time 
british environment secretary chris patten also refused to rule 
out britains storing nuclear waste under the seabed 
danish environment minister lone dybkjaer said the conference 
ended in a furious row on this issue and he accused britain of 
betraying the lives of future generations 
the twoday conference was the third in a series that began in 
1984 in the west german port of bremen a followup meeting was 
held in london in 1987 
participants were the netherlands belgium france britain 
west germany switzerland denmark norway and sweden as well as 
the european commission the eecs executive body ten other 
nations among them east germany and czechoslovakia had observer 
status 
it was a very very tough conference and the results dont go 
far enough for us particularly in the field of sewage treatment 
said west german environment minister klaus toepfer 
but we signed the final document because it will bring us a 
step further in the international field toepfer told reporters 
here 
on wednesday britain underwent a barrage of criticism because 
of its failure to meet the 1990 deadline for halting sea dumpings 
of industrial waste as had been agreed on in london in 1987 
the british contend they need time to convert their industrial 
plant to landbased waste treatment they also claim that most of 
the waste is not hazardous to the marine environment anyway 
during extremely tough negotiations thursday patten refused to 
budge on the issue conference sources said 
on the question of nitrates and phosphates the cause of massive 
blooms of algae along the north seas coast the conference decided 
to stick to its 1987 pledge to cut in half emissions of those 
substances by 1995 
 
