<TEXT>
top finance officials from the worlds seven 
largest industrial countries will meet in paris early next month to 
discuss turbulence in global currency markets and dramatic 
developments in eastern europe officials confirmed thursday 
the special talks involving the united states japan west 
germany britain france italy and canada were seen as an effort 
to strengthen economic coordination between the major industrial 
countries at a time of dramatic change in world affairs 
treasury secretary nicholas brady who was instrumental in 
scheduling the meeting insisted that there was no special 
urgency for the gathering of finance ministers and central bank 
presidents of the seven countries the talks are scheduled for 
april 7 
however the discussions will occur just one month before these 
same officials were scheduled to meet for a regular economic review 
session in conjunction with the spring meeting of the international 
monetary fund in washington 
currency markets have been especially volatile in recent weeks 
with the west german mark and the japanese yen falling in price 
while the us dollar has strengthened in value 
private economists predicted that the dollars strength and the 
corresponding weakness of the yen and the mark would be a key topic 
of discussion at the meeting 
analysts said that the rising dollar threatened to worsen an 
already huge american trade deficit by making foreign products less 
expensive for us consumers while making american goods more 
expensive on overseas markets 
the dollars strength is of great concern to the 
administration said allen sinai chief economist of the boston 
co it constitutes a recession threat because it is a further 
risk to an already beleaguered industrial side of the us 
economy 
the dollars advance has occurred despite coordinated 
intervention by the united states and other governments to sell 
dollars on foreign exchange markets and buy other currencies 
some analysts suggested that since government intervention has 
proved largely unsuccessful the g7 officials might discuss 
coordinated changes in interest rates 
higher interest rates in japan and west germany would tend to 
bolster their currencies while lower interest rates in the united 
states would make dollardenominated investments less attractive 
</TEXT>
