the blue moon tavern doesnt qualify as a 
cultural landmark and hundreds of longtime patrons are left 
crying in their beer 
the 56yearold taverns lease runs out in four years and after 
that landowner westlake capital corp plans to tear it down and 
build a sixstory housing and shopping development spokesman 
robert hannah told the seattle landmarks preservation board on 
wednesday night 
when the eight members of the 11person board present were 
evenly divided on whether to grant landmark status dozens of 
tavern supporters sporting blue moon stickers let out a collective 
groan the proposal needed six votes to pass 
the forever blue moon committee pushed for landmark status as 
the only way to save the establishment from the wrecking ball 
what the landmarks board has effectively done is say it will 
not designate any cultural landmarks in seattle said walt 
crowley a television commentator and former mayoral aide who 
helped organize the 1500member committee 
if the blue moon does not qualify i cannot imagine what 
could crowley said 
