a childrens advocacy group asked on thursday 
that regulators require broadcasters and cable tv operators show 
antismoking messages on youthoriented programs if they televise 
sports events sponsored by cigarette companies 
action for childrens television which was instrumental in 
reviving advertising limits for saturday morning childrens tv 
shows asked the federal communications commission to close a 
loophole in a 1969 law that banned cigarette advertising from 
television 
the group said cigarette companies got around the ban after it 
went into effect in 1971 ban by sponsoring televised sports events 
such as tennis tournaments and car races making their brands part 
of the names of the events 
act said tv cameras also routinely show billboards advertising 
cigarettes behind the sports action being shown act called them 
hidden commercials that subverts the purpose of the 1969 law 
congress passed the law because it had concluded that it is 
not in the public interest to have cigarettes advertised over such 
unique media that reach into every household and are particularly 
viewed by the young act told the fcc 
the young are being bombarded over television by hidden 
messages associated with sports that are meant to show that 
smoking is attractive act president peggy charren said in an 
interview 
