unescos director thursday defended his 
controversial restructuring plan for the agency after drawing 
criticism from us and other western diplomats 
director general federico mayor on feb 28 established 24 new 
management posts and promoted 18 top officials including many who 
came from the senior staff of his predecessor amadou mahtar mbow 
of senegal 
mayor appointed the former deputy director of the soviet state 
commission for radio and television henrikh yushiavitshus to the 
sensitive post of deputy director general for communications 
it had been expected that mayor would give the communications 
post to a westerner as part of his campaign to induce the united 
states and britain to rejoin the organization which they left in 
the mid1980s 
another soviet boris kluchnikov was proposed as director for 
europe a post that normally goes to a western or a neutral 
european 
the united states and britain which had provided about 30 
percent of the budget of the un education scientific and cultural 
organization left the agency because they claimed it was 
antiwestern poorly managed and spending too much 
western and japanese diplomats and the head of the us observer 
mission to parisbased unesco richard t miller called mayors 
plan a mistake a japanese delegate said it showed unesco was 
going backwards at great speed 
