reflected the changing political climate it had inspired through 
recent reforms 
asked whether the appointments were insensitive to british and 
american interests mayor said i cannot follow the sensibilities 
of any countries i have 161 countries 
i have chosen all my staff according to their personal 
qualifications and professional achievments i dont take into 
account their belonging to official systems that were in the past 
imposed in some countries he said 
diplomats and british news reports said mayor made his decision 
without consulting unescos executive board mayor said this was 
true but was his right as the director general of the organization 
mayor succeeded mbow in 1987 and promised major reforms 
including a new communications strategy aimed at toning down a 
unesco program critics saw as a threat to press freedom 
mayor said he received no political pressure from britain the 
united states or the soviet union when making appointments 
japan is now the largest contributor to unesco providing 16 
percent of its 370 million twoyear budget mayor said the soviet 
union was the second largest donor 
