<TEXT>
a san francisco group that organized 
underground tests of an aids drug derived from chinese cucumber 
roots won government approval to resume testing with a purified 
form of the drug an official of the group said thursday 
project inform an aids treatment and education group planned 
to announce friday that the food and drug administration has 
approved its application to conduct tests of the drug known as 
compound q on about 100 patients said terry beswick research 
director of the group 
an fda official who spoke on the condition of anonymity 
confirmed the approval and said it brings project inform under the 
agencys sanctioned clinical trials system assuring that the 
groups plan conforms to government standards for testing 
it gives the agency more control over the situation than it 
had before the fda official said we had problems with the 
secret trials whether the compound was pure what problems 
might be with the dose who was taking it that sort of thing this 
gives us a handle on that 
working with project inform to come up with a study design that 
meets fda requirements was a better alternative than trying to put 
the group out of business the official said 
how would you stop people from taking this drug if they really 
wanted it youre talking about quite an effort that might not be 
successful the official said this way were assured a good 
hard look at dose and safety 
last may project inform secretly organized a compound q study 
without fda authorization the groups leaders said they couldnt 
wait for the government because desperate aids patients were 
already experimenting with the drug 
doctors in the study infused their patients with compound q the 
name given to trichosanthin a protein from the root of a 
cucumberlike plant that chinese doctors have used for centuries to 
induce abortions and treat cancer the group used couriers to 
import the drug from china 
by the time the fda told project inform to discontinue the 
unapproved experiments last august the group had finished treating 
patients with the drug and had begun to evaluate their data 
in september martin delaney codirector of project inform 
said early results showed the drug holds promise but also has 
serious risks associated with it in earlier testtube studies the 
drug appeared to selectively kill cells infected with the aids 
virus 
in the secret tests about 60 patients were given infusions of 
compound q by doctors in san francisco new york miami and los 
angeles according to project inform officials two patients died 
during the trial and three others suffered severe dementia or 
seizures but recovered delaney said doctors did not believe the 
drug caused the deaths 
under the new study approved by the fda the groups research 
arm project informcommunity research alliance will test a highly 
purified form of compound q on up to 100 patients who previously 
were treated with the chinese import beswick said 
the fda source said the patients in the new study will be 
limited to those who were connected to project informs earlier 
underground study 
but beswick said others besides those who participated in the 
earlier study could participate he said hundreds of other 
people have been treated with the chinese version in underground 
experiments 
the purified form of the drug called glq223 was developed at 
the university of california at san francisco and genelabs of 
redwood city calif 
this version of the drug is being studied on patients in 
fdaapproved tests that were started at san francisco general 
hospital last may 
