more than half of national forests lost money 
on timber sales last year the government said thursday in a report 
that environmentalists say support their call to roll back 
subsidized timber sales 
the us forest service in its annual report on timber sales 
from the nations wilderness said profits on all the national 
forests rose 4 percent last year even though the total harvest 
declined about 5 percent 
there were 119 billion board feet of timber harvested from 
national forests last year after 126 billion board feet were 
harvested in 1988 and a record 127 billion board feet the year 
before 
overall the forest service said the government took in 15 
billion through timber sales in 1989 operating expenses for the 
timber sales program were 7767 million last year and the 
government paid states 3391 million for a net sales gain of 
4027 million up from 3886 million the previous year 
the timber sale program in which private companies pay the 
federal government for the right to harvest trees and a portion 
goes to states to build roads and schools generated about 132371 
jobs and 44 billion in personal income in fiscal 1989 the forest 
service said 
of the nations 122 national forests 66 of them lost money by 
selling timber at below cost the report said 
but george leonard associate chief of the service said those 
66 forests account for only 18 percent of the total volume of 
timber cut or about 2 billion board feet 
the forests where we lost the money are the small forests 
he said oregon and washington are responsible for about half the 
revenue and they produce about half the timber 
timber industry leaders said the net gain in sales shows the 
program is in good shape but environmentalists said the losses on 
the majority of the forests show the government is subsidizing 
private logging activities 
the hundreds of millions of dollars the forest service loses 
on subsidized timber sales are nothing more than public welfare for 
the logging industry said tom kuhnle an economist for the 
natural resources defense council 
he said the report should aid the bush administrations proposal 
to slowly eliminate subsidized sales at 12 national forests 
but david ford vice president of the public timber council of 
the national forest products association said the report proves 
the programs financial soundness 
the timber program is rare among federal programs in that it 
consistently earns money for the government he said 
the pacific northwest harvested by far the largest volume of 
timber last year with 52 billion board feet 
only the pacific northwest and southwest among the services 
eight regions posted actual profits last year based on timber sales 
after payments were made to states for such things as schools and 
roads 
