<TEXT>
the exxon valdez ran aground on a 
jagged reef and spilled its cargo of oil because the helmsman 
failed to turn the ship as far as he was ordered an expert 
testified thursday on behalf of the tankers skipper 
peter shizume who devised a complex computer program used to 
simulate ship accidents said the tanker would have gone past bligh 
reef in prince william with room to spare if the rudder had been 
turned only half as far as called for by the third mate 
i think the problem was the rudder was initiated late and not 
enough rudder was used shizume testified at the criminal trial 
of fired exxon skipper joseph hazelwood in the nations worst oil 
spill 
shizume who said he used various formulas to track the course 
of the tanker said it would have missed bligh reef by about two 
miles if the helmsman had turned 10 degrees right about 10 minutes 
before the ship ran aground and spilled nearly 11 million gallons 
of crude oil 
shizume from hicksville ny said as little as 5 degrees less 
than five minutes before the accident also would have saved the 
ship 
the third mate who was in control of the exxon valdez while 
hazelwood went to his cabin testified earlier in the trial that 10 
minutes before the accident he called for the helmsman to execute 
10 degrees right rudder 
the mate suggested that the helmsman robert kagan failed to 
follow the order because he had problems with steering and had once 
been reprimanded for steering too hard 
shizume said his study of the ships course recorder showed that 
kagans average turn during the critical period was 4 degrees 
what is your opinion as to what he was doing asked attorney 
michael chalos 
he looks like he was swinging the rudder back and forth 
apparently without any commands to do so shizume said 
shizume a physicist and engineer retired from sperry gyroscope 
co said he was hired to create the mockup system used at the 
national maritime research center at kings point ny the system 
is used for training captains and studying shipping accidents 
hazelwood 43 is on trial on four criminal counts stemming from 
the march 24 grounding of the exxon valdez in prince william sound 
he faces up to 7 years in prison and 61000 in fines if convicted 
on all four counts 
in other testimony a naval architect challenged the testimony 
of a prosecution expert saying the exxon valdez wouldnt have sunk 
if hazelwood had been able to work it off the reef immediately 
after the spill 
the prosecution contends that by engaging the engines and 
turning the rudder from side to side hazelwood put the ship in 
danger of capsizing and further damaged the part of the tanker that 
was resting on rock 
edward hoffman the naval architect said hazelwoods crew would 
have been able to keep the ship from capsizing by transferring sea 
water into oil tanks to balance the ships load 
hoffman also testified that he examined the wrecked exxon valdez 
at its dry dock in san diego and concluded that hazelwoods actions 
after it went aground didnt further damage to the tanker 
my opinion is that the explosive impact with the ship and the 
reef caused the majority of damage hoffman said subsequent to 
that the rise and fall of the tide caused further damage 
hoffman led off the second day of defense testimony after 
hazelwoods lawyers moved to center stage in the criminal trial 
