portauprince haiti ap thousands of demonstrators across 
haiti set up flaming tire barricades and burned cars to protest the 
armys killing of a schoolgirl three people were killed including 
a soldier beaten to death by a mob 
two people were hospitalized with bullet wounds and at least 10 
others were injured in clashes with soldiers 
about 3000 people shouting liberty and slogans against 
haitis leader lt gen prosper avril converged in downtown 
portauprince near the national palace after attending a memorial 
service on the outskirts of the capital for 11yearold roseline 
vaval shot to death by the army monday 
about 10000 people turned up for her burial thursday in the 
small town of petit goave 
along the road leading to petit goave outside the town of 
carrefour about 3000 protesters burned automobiles including a 
police car and erected barricades of flaming tires 
the independent radio metropole said a soldier and a civilian 
was killed in the carrefour clashes it said a mob carrying sticks 
and stones dragged a passing soldier from his motorcycle and beat 
him to death 
the radio said the killing was in reprisal for the earlier 
killing of a civilian by a presidential guardsman 
avril who came to power in september 1988 in a coup led by 
rankandfile soldiers has been under increasing pressure from 
opposition groups to resign 
the will of the people is for avril to step down said a 
communique released thursday night by a coalition of 11 opposition 
parties which had called on haitians to rise against avril 
businesses closed and people poured into the streets pounding 
pots and pans garbage cans and metal poles after students called a 
day of mourning for the girl shot by a soldier breaking up an 
antigovernment demonstration 
maj gen serge sainteloi the inspector general of the army 
said thursday night that a soldier from a passing vehicle shot the 
girl but there would be no investigation because her parents buried 
her before an autopsy could be conducted 
a spokeswoman for the haitian christian democratic party 
speaking on condition of anonymity said three soldiers barged into 
the party headquarters near the national palace on thursday and 
beat three party members with their rifle butts 
president bush remarked on the haitian situation on thursday 
while attending a ceremony in fort myer va marking the us 
invasion of panama 
bush said the revolution continues the people have spoken in 
nicaragua when they speak in cuba and haiti our western 
hemisphere will be entirely within the compass of freedom 
the opposition in nicaragua backed by the united states 
defeated president daniel ortega and his ruling sandinistas in feb 
25 elections 
in haitis capital protesters leaving the memorial in the slum 
neighborhood of bel air left flaming tires at nearly every 
crossroad along the 1mile route into the city 
a crowd then made its way to a cemetery for her burial and 
soldiers used truncheons and fired into the air to disperse about 
1000 protesters one unidentified man was killed a few feet from 
the army headquarters 
a doctor at the state hospital said 12 people were injured 
including two who suffered gunshot wounds 
reports surfaced of studentled demonstrations in several 
provincial cities in the fourth day of protest against the 
government schools were closed throughout the country 
radio haitiinter reported the army high command had ordered 
soldiers to use restraint in quelling unrest 
in an interview wednesday avril indicated he would consider 
resigning saying i will never resist the will of the people 
but he said if i step down hurriedly it will create a lot of 
turmoil 
general elections are scheduled this year but virtually all 
opposition parties have promised to boycott them unless avril first 
steps down they say he is not to be trusted with holding free 
elections or handing over power to civilians 
the parties also want avril to be replaced by a supreme court 
justice until a new leader is elected 
avril has said he is not interested in running for office and 
urged his opponents to put aside differences and get on with 
elections 
in protests reminiscent of the demonstrations in november 1985 
to protest the armys killing of three high school students 
thousands of students have been marching since monday in the 
provincial towns of jacmel jeremie leogane petit goave and 
mirebalais 
the 1985 student protests led to downfall of dictator 
jeanclaude duvalier who fled to exile in france in february 1986 
avril later ousted lt gen henri namphy who succeeded duvalier 
in november 1987 during the first free elections since haiti 
became independent from france in 1804 attackers protected by 
soldiers killed at least 34 voters at the polls and the elections 
were called off 
</TEXT>
