<TEXT>
reporters and columnists withheld their bylines 
from the pages of the st louis postdispatch on wednesday one day 
before contract negotiations were to resume between the newspaper 
and its unions 
about 600 members of local 47 of the st louis newspaper guild 
have been working without a contract since their old pact expired 
at midnight feb 28 
the guild is the largest of 11 unions at the newspaper and is 
one of six unions that have not reached agreement on a new contract 
herb goodrick executive director of the local said he was 
pleased with the number of writers who had withheld their bylines 
in the first byline strike in the papers history 
its been very effective said goodrick its to show that 
theyre embarrassed to put their name on a paper that takes the 
bargaining position that the post has taken theyre ashamed of it 
and dont want their name tied to it 
postdispatch publisher nicholas penniman said only that the 
writers were within their rights to withhold their bylines under 
their current contract 
the labor dispute comes at a particularly sticky time for the 
postdispatch which is no longer the only daily newspaper in town 
thanks to last falls startup of the nonunion st louis sun by 
ingersoll publications co of princeton nj 
postdispatch unions have urged a boycott of the sun which on 
tuesday denied admittance to goodrick an attorney and a reporter 
from the st louis labor tribune 
the postdispatch is owned by pulitzer publishing co 
management and the union are at odds over a number of issues 
including the deletion of a 4 percent costofliving increase that 
was offered in a company proposal the union rejected last september 
the latest company offer would also deny sick leave to employees 
who contract illnesses through immorality 
other unresolved issues include a lengthy managment rights 
clause maternity leave union rights employee drug testing and a 
twotier wage system which would pay new hires lower wages 
goodrick said the union has not threatened a strike against the 
newspaper 
at this point weve tried to be very restrained and 
responsible he said our objective is to get an agreement a 
strike is one of the tools for that but we think there are other 
steps we can take before that 
id like to reach an agreement in the next couple of days 
goodrick said but if we dont we cant just sit around twiddling 
our thumbs we have to do something to motivate people 
</TEXT>
