<TEXT>
brazil is mired in its worst 
economic crisis as it takes the final step to full civilian 
democracy with the inauguration thursday of its first popularly 
elected president in 30 years 
he is the conservative fernando collor de mello who likens 
himself to a hunter with a single bullet left and a hungry tiger 
coming at him 
the tiger is inflation and collar says he has to kill it with 
one quick shot or be devoured 
but dont worry he adds confidently im an excellent 
shot and i wont miss 
inflation rose 56 percent in january and a record 73 percent in 
february with the projection of an annual rate of 71000 percent 
march is expected to be worse 
collor will replace president jose sarney who took over from a 
military government in 1985 but failed in a number of attempts to 
halt the nations economic and financial slide 
brazilians have lived for decades with inflation but have been 
protected by costofliving indexing of wages and bank accounts 
experts now say however such government protection may be at an 
end 
hyperinflation marks the demise of this socially exclusive 
elitist economic model it is the state of bankruptcy of the 
government edmar bacha an economist and former head of the 
governments census bureau said in an interview 
today bacha added this country of 150 million is what he calls 
a belindia a belgium and an india side by side 
the belgium half resembles a developed country with the western 
worlds eighthlargest economy and thirdbiggest trade surplus a 
world leader in the production of coffee sugar orange juice 
soybeans cotton and iron ore a producer and exporter of 
sophisticated goods such as computers cars aircraft and rockets 
the india part is marked by the third worlds largest foreign 
debt put at 114 billion 7 million street children 20 percent 
adult illiteracy sprawling shantytowns and epidemics of dengue 
malaria and yellow fever 
however the consensus is that inflation is the countrys most 
serious problem 
collors credibility and the viability of his government 
depend on how he deals with inflation said luiz antonio de 
medeiros president of the powerful metalworkers union all the 
other problems he will face income distribution the foreign 
debt poverty etcetera are secondary 
the economy has gone haywire at the hands of inflation 
in a rio department store a barbie doll costs more than 
februarys monthly minimum wage of 2004 cruzados 70 a linen 
shirt costs as much as six 3speed blenders identical knapsacks 
cost 600 cruzados 2150 at one store and 2400 cruzados 86 at 
another in the same shopping mall 
investors seek shelter in gold and illegal blackmarket dollars 
or in an extremely shortterm financial market known as the 
overnight which today pays 105 percent a month 
consumers rush to stock up on food clothes and electrical 
appliances before prices go up again 
violent crime is increasing and brazilians look anxiously to 
neighboring argentina where runaway inflation has led to the 
looting of supermarkets and military unrest as a example of what 
might be in store for them 
people are frightened said graciela treiyer the manager of 
an upscale leather goods boutique in rio de janeiro the 
government says inflation is 70 percent but we know its more 
things are just out of control 
an estimated 1 billion a month is leaving the country and 
muchneeded foreign investment has dried up 
one cant plan one cant contract one doesnt know how much 
supplies are going to cost or anything else with inflation so 
ridiculously high said william meissner president of the 
american chamber of commerce in rio de janeiro 
a growing number of brazilians are seeking financial safety in 
the united states western europe or japan 
we are not an island of prosperity with hyperinflation we 
are more like a continent of despair said sen roberto campos a 
former planning minister and exambassador to the united states and 
england 
some even are asking whether brazil was better off under the 
repressive military regime that ruled from 1964 to 1985 
sure weve got democracy now but what good is it when beans 
are 38 cruzados 137 a kilo said jose de oliveira a tax 
office worker who moonlights as a chauffeur at a car rental agency 
collors remedy is to drastically cut government spending he 
has promised to lay off workers close government ministries drop 
subsidies and sell off stateowned companies trade barriers will 
be lowered and protection for domestic industry eliminated 
however economists say brazil also will have to sharply reduce 
interest payments on its billiondollar foreign debt which amount 
to 12 billion a year 
collor says he will order the federal police to arrest the tax 
evaders middlemen and speculators he holds responsible for 
inflation 
the blame falls on the elite who take advantage of the 
economic and financial disorder to make more and more money in 
detriment of the vast majority of the population he told a 
recent news conference 
collor is banking on his popularity among the poor masses and 
his credibility as a popularly elected president sarney was 
chosen by an electoral college in december collor defeated 
socialist luis inacio lula da silva by 4 million votes in brazils 
first free presidential election since 1960 
however analysts say collor will meet stiff opposition from 
congress labor unions and the rich who risk losing longheld 
privileges 
the elite will use the unions economist bacha predicts 
inefficient and protected industries will claim theyll be forced 
to fire employees if the government allows imports its the same 
argument americans are used to hearing in relation to japanese 
competition 
congress is another stumbling block collors national 
reconstruction party founded just last year has only 26 seats in 
the 570seat legislature da silva his adversary in the election 
has pledged to form a parallel government with other leftists 
to oppose the new administration 
militant labor unions which backed da silva have threatened to 
strike if the government holds down wages or lays off workers 
collor doesnt have support in the organized sectors of 
society said eli diniz a political scientist at the university 
research institute of rio de janeiro he will have to negotiate a 
social pact to give his measures legitimacy or try a populist 
mobilization 
brazilians who have seen four antiinflation plans collapse in 
as many years under sarney are torn between hope and skepticism 
the people are rooting for collor and want to help but they 
will demand results said psychologist sigrid marques da silva 
castro 
in a february survey by the respected ibope polling institute 
68 percent of those questioned said they had faith in collor 
i hate to say it but im optimistic like a brazilian is 
optimistic said meissner of the american chamber of commerce 
brazils like a baby with a fever youre convinced the baby is 
going to die and two hours later its playing outside 
