<TEXT>
terry briggs has babysat housesat and 
dogsat learning along the way she couldnt just sit 
for eight years briggs worked at general motors corps buick 
city in flint birthplace of the largest us automaker in october 
1987 the company said she no longer had a job and that it probably 
wouldnt rehire her 
since then shes been trying to piece together a life on 
layoff a life of odd jobs overdue bills daytime tv handouts 
handiwork boredom and anxiety just when i think its not going 
to work somebody comes up with something said briggs 42 whose 
cheeriness belies her nagging nervousness about living from hand to 
mouth 
she is among thousands of americans who have been laid off from 
jobs in auto assembly component and supplier plants which are 
struggling because of a recession in the auto industry 
factories have closed work has dried up and people like briggs 
in the nebulous category of too young to retire and too old to find 
a new job are scrambling to pay bills 
for briggs working for gm has come back to haunt her 
the job search hasnt been good for me she says im a 
fat 40 yearold female and a general motors employee she says 
some potential employers shy away from gm workers because they 
are too spoiled they want money they want benefits 
pay and benefits can be worth more than 40000 a year to 
autoworkers who have some overtime many of those laid off often 
balk at the prospect of looking hard for a job that pays less 
barbara jubar a clinical social worker with catholic social 
services in flint where many autoworkers are unemployed says they 
often resist training for another profession 
why should i train to do something that is onethird of what i 
made before she says quoting a common response among her 
clients i think its just a reluctance to think more longterm 
clarence cobb of detroit was among 1700 workers who lost their 
jobs feb 2 when chrysler corp shut its famous jefferson avenue 
plant once a symbol of chryslers might but now relegated to the 
scrap heap hes a 22year oldtimer with chrysler but a youngster 
in the layoff ranks 
it hasnt set in yet cobb 42 says his wifes salary from 
her job as a district court supervisor in detroit helps pay the 
bills 
cobb watches a lot of tv soap operas are his favorites hes 
going to be a grandfather soon and thats sure to take up some of 
his time he said 
cobb might return to work next year when chrysler begins 
training employees to build a sportutility vehicle at a new 
factory rising beside the hulk of the jefferson avenue plant but 
his job prospects are uncertain 
its a waiting game right now cobb says 
for many autoworkers the waiting game is nerveracking partly 
because they dont know how long their money will last 
cobb briggs and others on layoff were eligible for unemployment 
and other payments including a supplemental unemployment benefit 
tailored for autoworkers and designed to yield up to 95 percent of 
their preovertime takehome pay with so many layoffs this year 
however the sub funds are shrinking 
i never got 95 percent of my wages briggs says they 
dropped it down to 75 percent the day i was laid off because of the 
strain on the sub fund i was ok while i still had the sub 
when her sub allotment ran out in april 1988 briggs says she 
filed for bankruptcy protection 
that was the most difficult thing ive ever done she says 
the humiliation just doesnt go away 
studies have documented increased cases of alcoholism drug 
abuse and family problems among laidoff workers mainly because of 
the stress a job loss puts on individuals and their relationships 
with loved ones 
to understand the process that a laidoff employee goes 
through you must understand that our jobs and our selfconfidence 
are very intertwined says dr nyk bartkiw director of 
outpatient services at a community mental health program in 
michigans genesee county where many laidoff autoworkers live 
the first reaction is that im a nobody i dont have a job 
anymore bartkiw says we have to help them get over that 
first step you are more than a job 
briggs has performed a constant juggling act trying to channel 
whatever income she can scrape together toward the final notice 
bill with the earliest due date 
she still owes money on her 1986 chevrolet nova a car that sits 
with a blown engine her apartment rent is supplemented by general 
assistance welfare money and her landlady is lending a hand with 
utility bills 
she used to sew but her assemblyline work led to carpel tunnel 
syndrome a handweakening affliction in factory workers who 
perform the same tasks repetitively clothesmaking is out 
other people pay some of her bills often on what amounts to a 
barter system if she paid the bills in cash it might endanger her 
benefits which include 99 a month in food stamps and assistance 
with her 200amonth payments for heart and diabetes medicine 
i have a friend who has a dog and when she goes away i go 
housesit and dogsit for her and then she pays my rent or 
whatever briggs says thats kind of hard because shes a dear 
friend and i really dont like her doing that 
briggs has given of herself too she recently helped deliver 
christmas baskets to the needy with other members of a masonic 
lodge 
man i was ashamed of myself for even worrying about me 
because every house i went to was worse than the last one she 
said i think the thing is that nobody cares about them there 
are a few of us who do but not nearly enough 
