<TEXT>
five years time enough for a world to change years enough for 
a newborn to sprout into girlhood nights enough for a man caged 
to sink into dark despair and then sink deeper still 
five years ago this friday on march 16 1985 associated press 
correspondent terry a anderson was shoved into the back seat of a 
mercedes and driven off into the black hole of beirut he remains a 
hostage today longestheld of eight american and 10 other western 
hostages in lebanon 
anderson now 42 last spoke to the world 16 months ago in a 
videotape released by the moslem extremists who hold him in a gray 
track suit cleanshaven he looked stronger than in the past but 
the spirit was bleak 
as the end of my fourth year approaches he said i find 
it difficult to keep my hopes and my courage high 
now the end of his fifth year approaches 
hopes so often crushed are rising again andersons tireless 
sister peggy say recently returned from a middle east journey 
with ap officials and spoke of a feeling of hope rumors of 
secret talks are flying through europe the president of iran the 
nation believed to hold sway over the lebanese kidnappers says he 
feels the hostage crisis is moving toward a solution 
somewhere in the rubble of lebanon anderson and the 17 others 
are imprisoned apparently held in small rooms chained often 
blindfolded deprived of sunlight deprived of faith lost in a 
hopelessness that at one point drove anderson to pound and bloody 
his head against a wall 
the meaning of five years of inhuman captivity each year a 
neareternity is beyond imagining but a simple measure of time 
can be taken 
on the day anderson was kidnapped mikhail gorbachev was in his 
first week of power in moscow ronald reagan had not yet met a 
soviet leader marcos and duvalier still ruled chernobyl still 
operated the challenger astronauts still drilled for their fateful 
flight 
while anderson endured his pains wars yielded to peace enemies 
embraced as friends history remade the worlds landscape while 
anderson lay in chains his second daughter sulome was born and 
grew into a lively 4yearold a girl deprived of a fathers warmth 
the senior hostage is also the youngest hostage and perhaps 
the bestknown among an american group that also includes 
scottishborn poetryloving academic thomas sutherland accountant 
and moslem convert joseph cicippio adventurous schoolmaster frank 
herbert reed sometimewriter edward tracy journalism professor 
alann steen business teacher and diabetic robert polhill and 
math professor jon turner 
anderson the reporter now locked up by moslem militants in a 
makeshift dungeon had once huddled with fearful moslems in other 
basements under christian bombardment there to tell their story 
to the world 
a harddriving selfassured journalist the aps chief middle 
east correspondent covered lebanons endless tragedy with grit and 
aplomb jazz blared from his automobile tape deck as he dashed from 
crisis to crisis 
covering lebanon sometimes meant having to drive through one 
war to get to the war youre covering he explained 
anderson brought a broad reporting background to lebanon he 
covered desegregation in kentucky the struggle for democracy in 
south korea the fight for racial justice in south africa 
not taciturn but judicious with words not unfriendly but 
serious about the task at hand anderson took on journalism with 
the discipline of a marine his onetime calling i like where 
im at he told a nephew who interviewed him for a school 
assignment 
a day after anderson was grabbed off a beirut street by four 
gunmen an anonymous caller reported he was being held by islamic 
jihad islamic holy war an underground shiite moslem group 
that had begun kidnapping westerners a year earlier 
six other americans and britons were already held by islamic 
jihad and other shadowy bands in lebanon four eventually were 
freed the two others died in captivity 
in the months that followed other americans frenchmen britons 
and west germans one by one sometimes two by two were 
kidnapped by extremists trying to strike out at western governments 
they considered to be always on the wrong side of the mideasts 
many conflicts 
islamic jihads goal was a trade its hostages for 17 islamic 
jihad comrades imprisoned in kuwait for bombing the us and french 
embassies there otherwise it said it would execute its 
captives 
but president reagan vowed no concessions no deals 
periodically the hostage impasse seemed to move toward 
resolution as when negotiations on iranian assets frozen in the 
united states made major progress last year but the low points far 
outnumbered the high 
in june 1986 cancerstricken glenn anderson jr made a 
videotape appeal from his sickbed for his brother terrys freedom 
four days later he died four months earlier their father glenn 
also was lost to cancer terry anderson apparently has never been 
informed of either death 
in november 1986 the irancontra affair exploded it was 
disclosed the reagan administration had arranged secret arms 
shipments to iran via israel that apparently led to hostage 
releases the resulting political firestorm shut down this 
backchannel dealing 
one of the hardest blows came in january 1987 anglican church 
official terry waite a longtime mediator in the crisis dropped 
from sight in beirut a victim himself of the kidnappers 
at one point islamic jihad mocked those who dared hope 
what everyone expects soon is a mirage assumed to be water by 
a thirsty man it said in a statement in mid1988 
life as a hostage according to the freed men is a relentless 
monotony punctuated by moments of terror and dread 
they were moved periodically blindfolded and at night 
sometimes they were confined alone sometimes thrown into cramped 
rooms together they were chained to walls or fixtures and were 
allowed only brief minutes in a bathroom each day 
they fought the maddening monotony through exercise talk and 
reading of a battered bible and a handful of other overworked 
books sometimes they cried but they also dreamed prayed planned 
terry was always creating things his farm his restaurant 
his house said the rev lawrence jenco a released hostage 
terry anderson is a unique and gifted person 
the freed hostage who last saw anderson frenchman marcel 
fontaine released in 1988 remembers the americans courage 
when i was a little sick and dispirited fontaine recalled 
i said to terry that im not afraid to die but i dont want to 
die here and have them throw my body into the sea 
anderson thought a moment he said and replied i dont want 
to die anywhere 
family friends colleagues and other supporters gather friday 
in ceremonies in washington and elsewhere to reaffirm their faith 
in the eventual release of anderson and the other hostages 
and they will pray that anderson himself after five pitiless 
years may still find some faith and comfort in his own worn 
bible perhaps or even in his jailers koran the holy book whose 
sura 94 reassures the tormented that verily with every 
difficulty there is relief 
