<TEXT>
the industry lost 115 billion in the first nine months of last 
year on track to break the record 134 billion loss for all of 
1988 
meanwhile stringent new financial standards in last summers 
legislation are forcing savings institutions to shrink 
the rules require thrifts to back their lending with more of 
their owners money most cant raise the capital as a result 
they must trim their balance sheets 
excluding interest 74 billion in deposits poured out of sampls 
last year at first because the industrys problems had shaken 
customers confidence later because thrifts sold assets and no 
longer needed the deposits 
big is no longer beautiful in the savings and loan business 
said analyst kenneth h thomas of miami 
those that cannot downsize successfully an estimated 180 to 
250 will fail bringing the governments caseload to nearly 600 
institutions by the end of this year analysts predict fewer than 
2400 solvent sampls will remain down from 3200 only three years 
ago 
the survivors have little reason to welcome 1990 weak real 
estate markets have spread from the oilproducing states of texas 
oklahoma louisiana and colorado to nearby arizona and to the 
northeast particularly new england 
the demise of drexel burnham lambert inc and the nearcollapse 
of the junk bond market also threatens a handful of big thrifts 
a month ago centrust savings bank of miami became the first sampl 
to fail because of junk bond losses it was followed by imperial 
savings association of san diego which had the industrys 
secondlargest junk bond portfolio 
thomas said columbia savings and loan association of beverly 
hills calif with the largest junk bond holdings around 4 
billion is shaky too 
congress which produced the sampl bill in what for it was a 
headlong rush of six months likely will spend 1990 evaluating its 
handiwork rather than fixing it 
proposals for change abound and theyll get an airing this 
month in hearings before the house banking subcommittee on 
financial institutions chaired by rep frank annunzio dill 
builders complaining they cant get loans are pushing for 
relaxation of new restrictions on the amount of money an sampl can 
lend to one borrower thrift executives want congress to ease rules 
forcing them to concentrate more heavily in mortgage lending 
rep bruce vento dminn introduced a bill that would abolish 
the rtc oversight board sen bob kerrey dneb would make the 
rtc independent of both the administration and fdic 
reps charles schumer dny and leach want to do away with 
the thrift office and divide its duties 
sen richard bryan dnev submitted legislation to forbid 
financial institutions from selling their uninsured debt to their 
depositors 
debate also is starting on what many economists say is the most 
glaring deficiency of the legislation its failure to curb federal 
deposit insurance 
with accounts guaranteed to 100000 depositors have no reason 
to withdraw their money even when sampl and bank owners make wildly 
speculative investments the economists argue 
the treasury department congress general accounting office 
the fdic and trade groups all are working on proposals for reform 
unprodded by the administration however most legislators have 
little appetite for dealing with savings and loans during an 
election year 
those watching from the wings say the administration would be 
wise to press for change now rather than waiting until next year 
i think this administration still has the opportunity to 
distance itself from this problem said attorney john hawke a 
former federal reserve regulator now in private practice 
but its not going to be very long before it becomes their 
problem hawke said and at the next election all the voters 
are going to remember is the bush administration failed to clean 
it up 
