<TEXT>
call it skid wars the scientific quest for 
better ways to clear ice off roads is focusing on cracking it 
sabotaging it sandblasting it and even zapping it with microwaves 
roads that resist the tight grip of an ice patch are under 
study and under one strategy motorists would loosen ice just by 
driving on it 
the research is part of a 65 million program administered by 
the national research council an arm of the congressionally 
chartered national academy of sciences it is seeking alternatives 
to spreading salt which can pollute the environment and eat away 
at autos and prying ice with snowplow blades which takes lots of 
energy and chews up pavement 
scientists are aiming to design machines that remove ice while 
moving at 20 miles an hour as well as pavements that shed ice more 
easily results are preliminary but researchers say they see some 
promise 
one basic problem they face is that ice sticks tightly to a 
road both by chemical bonding and by interlocking with tiny 
crevices in the pavement 
ice binds more tightly to pavement than to itself which is why 
a snowplow blade can shear off the top of an ice patch without 
removing the layer that grips the road said albert wuori of the 
keweenaw research center of michigan technological university in 
houghton 
thats where the microwaves come in they can pass through ice 
and warm the pavement melting the thin layer of ice that touches 
the road surface 
all we want to do is destroy that bond between the ice and 
the pavement which then makes the rest of the ice very easy to 
remove wuori said trying to melt all the ice would take too 
much energy to be practical 
an experimental device with about 30 times the power of a home 
microwave oven has loosened ice from experimental pavement in the 
laboratory said jack monson of research associates of syracuse 
ny 
the process is too slow to be practical researchers hope that 
treating pavement surfaces with microwaveabsorbing materials will 
make them warm up faster and hasten the melting 
another strategy would use spikes to punch partway into icy 
patches and make them crack highpressure injections of antifreeze 
into the cracks might then be able to pry ice off the road said 
kazuhiko itagaki of the us army cold regions research and 
engineering laboratory in hanover nh 
if not injections of a deicer might weaken the ices grip on 
the pavement and make later removal easier wuori said 
research so far has shown pretty much success with a single 
spike plunger and it is now focusing on multiple plungers wuori 
said the holes would have to be punched inches apart he said 
still other approaches are more direct a sandblasting device 
has blown away strips of ice a halfinch thick in laboratory tests 
said mark osborne at the keweenaw center but it works much too 
slowly he said 
it might take multiple sandblasters or a rotary system like the 
brooms on street sweepers to cut a wide enough swath for practical 
use he said perhaps a sensor could let an iceremoval truck 
adjust the height of its nozzles according to the thickness of the 
ice so the spray will not harm pavement he said 
a similar device that uses liquid instead of air to carry 
abrasives has cut through four inches of ice without trouble said 
michael ohadi at the michigan school again a key challenge is to 
make such a system cover ground faster 
researchers have not given up on snowplow blades if they can 
work with less energy smaller trucks can be used saving on the 
sticker price and fuel consumption wuori said 
one energysaving goal is to make the bottom of the ice slab 
crack continuously ahead of the moving blade wuori said computer 
calculations are testing different blade shapes and angles of 
attack on the ice 
other studies focus on new kinds of pavement that would help 
break the grip of ice or prevent the stubborn bond from forming 
one plan involves motorists the weight of their vehicles might 
be deflected to shear ice off pavement computer calculations at 
the midwest research institute in kansas city mo show that 
patterns of ridges in the road might do the trick wuori said 
a similar strategy involves mixing bits of rubber with asphalt 
so that the pavement surface will bend a small fraction of an inch 
under the weight of a vehicle that action could tear ice away from 
the pavement wuori said 
researchers also are getting early glimmerings of success 
from mixing icefighting additives into asphalt before it is laid 
as pavement said bernard baum of springborn laboratories in 
enfield conn 
if the asphalt can resist strong bonding from ice icy patches 
will be easier to remove he said 
to be practical this special asphalt would have to work against 
ice for years the hope is that a continuing supply of additives 
would be available at the road surface brought up by migrating 
water and exposed as the surface wears down 
future work may find additives that can be spread on existing 
pavement which would be cheaper than mixing them in before laying 
asphalt he said so far the work has concentrated on asphalt 
which covers 90 percent to 95 percent of pavement in this country 
he said 
baum noted that to be useful icefighting additives would have 
to be environmentally safe and not weaken the pavement 
and one other thing 
you cant put anything on there that would be slippery he 
said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

