<TEXT>
us and japanese electronics industry groups 
proposed a joint plan thursday to boost us sales of 
semiconductors in japan 
a task force created by the us semiconductor industry 
association and the electronics industries association of japan 
recommended a variety of programs for increasing the us share of 
japans semiconductor market 
foreign semiconductor chips accounted for 129 percent of the 
japanese market in the last three months of 1989 according to the 
ministry of international trade and industry 
the task force composed of five japanese semiconductor user 
companies and six us suppliers called on nonjapanese chip 
makers to improve their sales and service in japan and to modify or 
redesign their semiconductors to meet japanese needs 
japanese companies have charged that us companies do not 
supply semiconductors that are suitable for the japanese consumer 
market 
the task force in a report said consumer electronics products 
account for more than a third of semiconductors used in japan but 
only 7 percent of those consumed in the united states 
the report said the five japanese user firms presented lists of 
the semiconductors used in some of their major consumer products 
us firms currently are able to supply about 6 percent of the 
semiconductors and after technical modifications to existing 
chips could supply about 12 percent of the japanese companies 
needs the report said 
the task force recommended that foreign suppliers be given a 
chance to demonstrate their technical and product development 
capabilities to achieve this it called for more exchange of 
technical information and for increased participation by foreign 
firms in the design of special semiconductors for products as they 
are being developed in japan 
semiconductors have been a focus of trade friction between the 
united states and japan since overcapacity in japan resulted in 
extensive pricecutting by competing japanese makers in the united 
states and elsewhere in the mid1980s 
in a 1986 bilateral semiconductor agreement japan pledged to 
stop selling chips in the united states at unfairly low prices and 
agreed to a goal of 20 percent of the japanese market for foreign 
semiconductors by july 1991 when the agreement expires japan has 
called the figure a target while us companies say it was a 
guarantee by japan 
in 1989 japanese makers held a 24 percent share of the us 
semiconductor market and 51 percent of the world market according 
to dataquest inc a us market research company 
</TEXT>
