<TEXT>
the chairman of the commodity futures 
trading commission today urged the futures industry to become more 
vocal in supporting the agencys fight to retain jurisdiction over 
stockindex futures 
in a speech to the annual meeting of the futures industry 
association here wendy gramm said futures exchange officials and 
trading firms must let congress know they object to the possible 
transfer of authority over index futures to the securities and 
exchange commission 
you must speak out to address these issues to educate the 
people who do not understand futures and options markets she 
said 
they must be made aware of your commitment to continue to be 
world leaders in terms of liquidity innovation and integrity 
despite tough talk by both mrs gramm and the chicago mercantile 
exchange the largest market for index futures the merc recently 
has indicated a greater willingness to compromise on the 
jurisdiction issue which surfaced in the aftermath of the 1987 
stock market crash 
the merc said last month in an outlook for the 1990s that it 
wanted to resolve regulatory issues surrounding stockindex 
futures merc chief leo melamed underscored the point at a news 
conference monday to announce his retirement plans 
were willing to sit down and get these issues behind us 
because these issues constantly drag us away from the business of 
business and that ought not to be said melamed chairman of the 
mercs executive committee 
but melamed also said that if that compromise means we give 
and no one else gives forget it 
the sec which regulates stock trading appears to be gaining 
congressional support for shifting regulatory control over index 
futures to the sec from the cftc 
the idea also has gained favor on wall street on tuesday 
robert downey a managing partner of goldman sachs amp co and 
chairman of the securities industry association told a senate 
subcommittee the sec should regulate both markets 
index futures allow investors to buy and sell the cash 
equivalent of baskets of stocks without ever owning the stocks 
themselves the merc trades futures on the standard amp poors 500 
stock index 
the sec started the regulatory tugofwar after the october 1987 
crash which some experts believe was worsened by computerdriven 
program trading techniques involving both the stock and stockindex 
futures markets 
mrs gramm disputed that claim in an unusually pointed speech 
three weeks ago in which she said individual investors had been 
leaving the stock market since the late 1960s so stockindex 
futures which arrived in the 1970s were not to blame for the 
recession on wall street 
critics of stockindex futures also have called for government 
authority to set the amount of margin or downpayment that 
investors must put down to buy or sell futures contracts 
mrs gramm believes the exchanges should be allowed to continue 
setting their own margins 
