in april 
the meeting of finance ministers and central bank presidents 
from the worlds most powerful industrial democracies the united 
states japan west germany britain france canada and italy 
would be the first such session since the dramatic changes in 
eastern europe 
an official who spoke on condition of anonymity said the 
united states had proposed the meeting to discuss how changes in 
eastern europe are affecting currency markets and the economic 
coordination efforts among the major powers 
in recent weeks the value of the dollar on world markets has 
climbed sharply while the japanese yen and west german mark have 
declined 
a stronger dollar threatens to worsen americas already huge 
trade deficit since it would make imports less expensive for 
american consumers and us products more expensive on overseas 
markets 
the g7 countries have been coordinating efforts this week to 
sell dollars and buy japanese yen and west german marks in an 
effort to dampen the dollars climb but so far the government 
currency sales have had limited impact 
in addition to the recent volatility in exchange markets the 
g7 officials were expected to address the question of the 
unification of west germany and east germany some economists fear 
this development could worsen inflationary problems in west 
germany especially if a proposal to exchange the west german 
currency for the east germany currency on a onetoone basis is 
carried out 
the april 7 meeting of the g7 countries will be held just one 
month before a previously scheduled may 7 meeting in washington 
