<TEXT>
opec secretarygeneral 
subroto said he expects the oil market to remain stable through 
spring according to a published report thursday 
demand for oil usually drops in spring we know the behavior 
of the market and the changes which accompany it but we expect 
there will be no changes said subroto in an interview with the 
staterun newspaper alittihad 
subroto who uses only one name spoke on the eve of the march 
16 meeting in vienna of the market monitoring committee of the 
13nation organization of petroleum exporting countries 
the cartel is committed to a production ceiling of 22 million 
barrels per day for the first six months of 1990 aimed at 
maintaining a reference price of 18 a barrel 
iraqi oil minister essam chalabi in an interview with the 
bahrainbased gulf news agency said he did not expect the meeting 
to make any substantial changes in the existing opec accord 
it is a meeting merely designed to take stock of the market 
without taking any decisions in its connection chalabi was 
quoted as saying this is a chance for the oil ministers to 
exchange views on the conditions of the oil market 
he said the full meeting of all 13 opec member will convene may 
25 with frequent consultations on stabilizing the market and 
maintaining the current market 
iraqs earlier call for a gradual increase in oil prices through 
limiting production contradicted the stand of producers like kuwait 
and the united arab emirates who have been calling for higher 
production 
hisham naser oil minister of saudi arabia the largest opec 
producer met with the iraqi and kuwaiti oil ministers earlier in 
the week they announced an agreement on a common policy to smooth 
the way for the opec meetings but no details had been disclosed 
oil prices reached well above the 18 mark in recent months due 
to the high demand for winter fuel 
subroto said the usual drop in demand would be offset by 
anticipated oil requirements of reforming eastern europe 
the soviet union was unable to meet the eastern european needs 
of oil in the last few years and these states will start looking 
for alternative sources of oil supplies subroto said 
he referred to deals already concluded between eastern europe 
and some opec member states but he did not go into detail 
subroto also said declining production in the united states and 
the soviet union could create a huge boost in demand in the next 
five years forcing an explosion in world prices if production 
capacity was not increased 
subroto of indonesia urged industrial states to help invest up 
to 60 billion to develop production capacity to meet demand 
current production capacity is 27 million barrels a day 
