<TEXT>
east german and foreign enterprises will be 
able to take stakes in private commercial banks when the country 
begins switching to a westernstyle banking system april 1 central 
bank director horst kaminsky said thursday 
kaminsky said the plan to switch to a western system approved 
thursday by the cabinet of the communistled interim government 
was an important move in making east germanys economy more 
compatible with west germanys with an eye toward eventual 
currency unification 
kaminsky who spoke at a news conference following the weekly 
cabinet meeting said foreign enterprises would be allowed to 
participate in the new banks but gave no details other than that 
the transformation would be gradual 
since the hardline communist leadership of erich honecker 
collapsed last fall the government has moved to make east 
germanys centrallyplanned economy more compatible with west 
germanys capitalist system as the countries move toward 
unification 
but east germanys economy has slowed drastically ahead of the 
countrys scheduled march 18 free elections which will seat a new 
parliament that could alter any decisions made by the interim 
government 
kaminskys proposal includes an autonomous central bank based 
on western models like west germanys bundesbank that will steer 
cash and credit in a mixed commercial banking sector 
kaminsky said a series of banks would be released from state 
ownership and an independent banking watchdog commission 
established 
the new banks would perform general commercial functions 
similar to west german banks he said they would include deutsche 
kreditbank ag genossenschaftsbank berlin ag deutsche 
aussenhandelsbank ag the east german foreign trade bank that 
already operates commercially abroad and cooperative banks for 
trades and crafts 
kaminsky said one consequence of the switch would be the 
emergence of a capital market and a stock exchange but he declined 
to say whether a bourse could be set up before the end of this year 
responding to questions about reports that east germanys 
foreign exchange reserves had dwindled recently from a total of 
176 billion to 940 million kaminsky said those rumors about 
our currency reserves do not represent the reality 
while admitting the uncertainty surrounding east germanys 
future may have unsettled some foreign creditors he stressed 
there is no cause for panic reports 
</TEXT>
