<TEXT>
northwest airlines plans to give away more 
freeflight coupons in hopes of appeasing passengers bumped on 
oversold flights 
in the first three months of this year the airline will reduce 
its rate of involuntarydenied boardings by 60 percent compared 
with a year earlier robert fornaro northwests vice president of 
marketing planning said wednesday involuntarydenied boardings 
are the bumping of passengers who dont want to get off planes 
in the fourth quarter of last year northwest involuntarily 
bumped about 2200 passengers or 253 for every 10000 passengers 
boarded 
northwest has been steadily improving by that measure since the 
problem peaked last summer the airline says in the fourth quarter 
of 1989 it bumped about 2500 fewer people than in the same 
quarter a year earlier and the bumpings were reduced even though 
total passenger boardings rose 12 percent 
northwests 1989 rate of involuntary bumpings was 383 per 
10000 passengers boarded down from 426 in 1988 said northwest 
spokesman doug miller 
the airline also showed progress in the fourth quarter in the 
number of people who are bumped voluntarily that means they 
take a later flight because the carrier offers them incentives such 
as cash or coupons for free flights in the future 
it costs us a few more free tickets but thats the price you 
pay fornaro said 
most major airlines aim to hold overbooking to a minimum in an 
effort to reduce both voluntary and involuntary bumping but when a 
flight is overbooked they want to convert as many travelers as 
possible to the voluntary side by offering them the freebies 
northwest offers freebies to bumped passengers now but it 
hasnt offered enough to entice larger numbers of fliers to give up 
their seats voluntarily 
fornaro said it is especially difficult for northwest to cut its 
number of involuntary bumpings because it has large numbers of 
passengers on long flights over the pacific passengers on longer 
flights are generally less flexible in their plans than those on 
shorter hauls 
many travelers especially business fliers reserve seats on 
several flights to ensure they will have their choice of departure 
times 
that forces airlines to book more reservations than they have 
seats or risk having lots of empty seats 
</TEXT>
