<TEXT>
here is a brief look at the major elements of 
the bush administrations national transportation policy released 
thursday 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the policy would preserve and maintain existing roads highways 
airports railroad lines waterways and other transportation 
facilities and focus on moving people and goods not simply 
vehicles in planning new systems expansion would be accomplished 
in partnership with state and local governments and private 
investors with federal programs focusing on projects of national 
significance 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the federal government would rely more heavily on user fees to 
finance its share and give state and local governments more 
authority to raise their own revenue through toll roads local gas 
taxes airport passenger taxes and other fees user fees are also 
proposed for coast guard services and railroad safety activities of 
the government 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the government would encourage competition by continuing to 
remove regulations including federal requirements on truck rates 
and services and on liability procedures affecting the railroad 
industry the transportation department also would review federal 
maritime programs and pursue international negotiations to help 
us shipping lines compete in world markets 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the government will launch a campaign to reduce highway traffic 
fatalities and will continue to address concerns about hazardous 
materials shipments aging airliners transportation vehicle design 
and the distribution and use of illegal drugs 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the policy recognizes the need for more fuelefficient vehicles 
the implications of global climate changes and the problems 
associated with aircraft noise but it recommends no specific 
action 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the federal government would provide some money to encourage 
research by private companies and educational institutions into 
magnetically levitated trains alternative power sources for cars 
hypersonic planes computerized vehicles and roads and other 
innovations 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

