<DOCNO> AP900308-0296 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the federal communications commission taking 
another big step towards a deregulated interstate longdistance 
phone business proposed thursday to loosen rules on atampt because 
the onetime monopoly company now faces significant competition 
the commission in a 40 vote adopted a staff proposal that if 
finally approved would give the american telephone amp telegraph co 
the freedom it says it needs to maneuver against some 500 
longdistance companies in the 55 billion longdistance 
marketplace 
the commission said it would study competition in the interstate 
longdistance arena and adopt necessary regulatory reforms but it 
tentatively concluded interstate services as a whole are now 
subject to significant competition and that competition in the 
provision of business services is particularly vigorous a key 
finding that must be made to deregulate atampt 
based on those conclusions the commission proposed a phasedin 
package of changes in certain business services extending later to 
800number services international calling and operator services 
the commission decided not to propose any changes to residential 
and small business services at this time 
the proposals are a victory for atampt which the fcc formally 
declared in 1981 as a dominant carrier that should be subject 
to regulation to prevent abuses to competitors or customers atampt 
won another victory last year when the fcc dumped its 20yearold 
rateofreturn regulation of atampts profits in exchange for a 
system that controls atampts prices within certain limits tied to 
the rate of inflation 
atampt has argued that it no longer is dominant and that it has 
lost 10 billion in business to competitors since the 1984 breakup 
of the old bell system prices have fallen 40 percent and its share 
of the longdistance market has dropped below 70 percent mci now 
has about 12 percent of the business us sprint about 9 percent 
and the rest is scattered among hundreds of smaller companies 
atampts arguments apparently fell on fertile ground at an fcc 
under new chairman alfred sikes who believes there is too much 
government intervention in the phone business 
the changes in market shares reflect the fact that competition 
has worked sikes said thursday 
sikes also said earlier this year the fcc would drop 
rateofreturn regulation on the interstate revenues of local 
telephone companies in 1991 and the commission issued proposed 
guidelines thursday for this new price cap regime 
besides capping prices the plan also would require the local 
phone companies to share any earnings above a certain level with 
customers 
atampt applauded the proposals for longdistance carriers saying 
the commission took a major step toward shaping policies based 
not on outdated orthodoxy but on future flexibility the fccs 
proposal validates atampts premise that everyone gains when all 
competitors are free to anticipate and meet customer needs 
competitors were less pleased with mci saying that while it too 
welcomed the fcc inquiry the fcc clearly recognizes that 
atampt can leverage its dominance to abuse competitors 
sprint said it was generally pleased with the fccs approach 
and that the fcc was appropriately moving towards deregulation 
where rules no longer are needed 
under current regulations atampt must make a public filing with 
the fcc each time it proposes to offer a new service or change the 
terms and conditions under which it offers any service already 
sanctioned by the fcc 
atampt says the public disclosure of its offerings and the length 
of time it takes to get fcc approval puts it at a disadvantage in 
todays fastmoving telecommunications marketplace 
the fcc apparently agreed proposing a streamlined filing 
process that would allow atampt to give one days notice for certain 
business services without submitting the cost data now required 
atampt also would be freed of some provisions of the new price 
cap regime the fcc imposed last year 
the fcc also proposed that atampt be permitted to offer certain 
business services to individual customers as long as they file 
contracts and summaries of their provisions within 30 days of the 
effective date of the contract 
the commission also proposed that all longdistance carriers be 
permitted to withdraw some of their facilities from the public 
phone network for use by private businesses 
the commission will ask public comment on its proposals and the 
opposition is expected to be strong from those who say atampt still 
has enormous market power and is likely to gain even more clout 
if it is deregulated 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900308-0297 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
witnesses at a congressional hearing on junk 
bonds warned thursday that defaults in the highrisk securities 
were likely to grow but did not necessarily think congress should 
act to restrict them 
representatives from the bond rating agencies moodys investors 
service and standard amp poors corp were among those testifying 
about the future and possible dangers of junk bonds before a 
subcommittee of the house energy and committee 
a junk bond is a shaky debt it is the promise to pay of a 
debtor who is just getting by said james grant editor of the 
newsletter grants interest rate observer 
bonds are in effect corporate promises to pay back borrowed 
money at a later date while paying a regular fixed interest junk 
bonds however are noninvestment grade meaning that rating 
services like sampp or moodys give them a greater chance of default 
than more stable investment grade bonds to compensate they pay a 
much higher interest yield 
pioneered by financier michael milken at the firm of drexel 
burnham lambert inc junk bonds helped a number of small or 
fledgling companies expand while also assisting corporate raiders 
in financing huge corporate takeovers with little upfront cash 
but the 200 billion junk bond market has been rocked repeatedly 
in recent months by milkens indictment on racketeering charges 
defaults by corporate junk borrowers the withdrawal of many 
savings and loan institutions as buyers of the securities and the 
bankruptcy filing by drexels parent company 
the subcommittees chairman rep edward markey dmass said 
there were questions about whether plunging prices in the junk 
market and the collapse of drexel had endangered the longterm 
health of us companies that rely on highyield financing 
the risks of the junk bond market have been exaggerated by the 
press said david wyss chief financial economist with 
drimcgrawhill adding that drexels demise is a symptom of the 
problems in the market more than a cause of new problems 
thomas j mcguire director of moodys corporate department 
said the default rate for speculativegrade bonds which includes 
junk bonds has risen to 54 percent the secondhighest rate since 
1970 
and the outlook given the increase in lower rated issuers 
and the potentially unfavorable economic environment is for still 
higher levels of defaults in the early 1990s mcguire said 
mark bachman senior vice president of sampps corporate finance 
department said current problems in the junk bond market are by 
no means inherent in the nature of all noninvestment grade bonds 
but rather stem from the excess of financial leverage that came to 
characterize junk bonds issuers in the late 1980s 
both grant and wyss cautioned against trying to correct the junk 
bond market through legislation 
i would advise the subcommittee to be wary of pushing the 
market toward even greater stringency said grant 
legislation is more likely to worsen than help the problem 
said wyss leverage is a response to the incentives in the tax 
law and unless those incentives change attacking the symptoms 
will just cause problems elsewhere 
